B001C032V025	1	32	25	And when he saw that he prevailed not against him, he touched the hollow of his thigh; and the hollow of Jacob's thigh was out of joint, as he wrestled with him.
B001C032V026	1	32	26	And he said, Let me go, for the day breaks. And he said, I will not let you go, except you bless me.
B001C032V027	1	32	27	And he said unto him, What is your name? And he said, Jacob.
B001C032V028	1	32	28	And he said, Your name shall be called no more Jacob, but Israel: for as a prince have you power with God and with men, and have prevailed.
B001C032V029	1	32	29	And Jacob asked him, and said, Tell me, I pray you, your name. And he said, Why is it that you do ask my name? And he blessed him there.
B001C032V030	1	32	30	And Jacob called the name of the place Peniel: for I have seen God face to face, and my life is preserved.
B001C032V031	1	32	31	And as he passed over Penuel the sun rose upon him, and he limped upon his thigh.
B001C032V032	1	32	32	Therefore the children of Israel eat not of the sinew which shrank, which is upon the hollow of the thigh, unto this day: because he touched the hollow of Jacob's thigh in the sinew that shrank.
B001C033V001	1	33	1	And Jacob lifted up his eyes, and looked, and, behold, Esau came, and with him four hundred men. And he divided the children unto Leah, and unto Rachel, and unto the two handmaids.
B001C033V002	1	33	2	And he put the handmaids and their children foremost, and Leah and her children after, and Rachel and Joseph last.
B001C033V003	1	33	3	And he passed over before them, and bowed himself to the ground seven times, until he came near to his brother.
B001C033V004	1	33	4	And Esau ran to meet him, and embraced him, and fell on his neck, and kissed him: and they wept.
B001C033V005	1	33	5	And he lifted up his eyes, and saw the women and the children; and said, Who are those with you? And he said, The children which God has graciously given your servant.
B001C033V006	1	33	6	Then the handmaidens came near, they and their children, and they bowed themselves.
B001C033V007	1	33	7	And Leah also with her children came near, and bowed themselves: and last came Joseph near and Rachel, and they bowed themselves.
B001C033V008	1	33	8	And he said, What mean you by all this drove which I met? And he said, These are to find grace in the sight of my lord.
B001C033V009	1	33	9	And Esau said, I have enough, my brother; keep what you have unto yourself.
B001C033V010	1	33	10	And Jacob said, Nay, I pray you, if now I have found grace in your sight, then receive my present at my hand: for therefore I have seen your face, as though I had seen the face of God, and you were pleased with me.
B001C033V011	1	33	11	Take, I pray you, my blessing that is brought to you; because God has dealt graciously with me, and because I have enough. And he urged him, and he took it.
B001C033V012	1	33	12	And he said, Let us take our journey, and let us go, and I will go before you.
B001C033V013	1	33	13	And he said unto him, My lord knows that the children are frail, and the flocks and herds with young are with me: and if men should overdrive them one day, all the flock will die.
B001C033V014	1	33	14	Let my lord, I pray you, pass over before his servant: and I will lead on slowly, according as the flocks that go before me and the children are able to endure, until I come unto my lord unto Seir.
B001C033V015	1	33	15	And Esau said, Let me now leave with you some of the folk that are with me. And he said, What need is there? let me find grace in the sight of my lord.
B001C033V016	1	33	16	So Esau returned that day on his way unto Seir.
B001C033V017	1	33	17	And Jacob journeyed to Succoth, and built him a house, and made booths for his cattle: therefore the name of the place is called Succoth.
B001C033V018	1	33	18	And Jacob came to Shalem, a city of Shechem, which is in the land of Canaan, when he came from Paddanaram; and pitched his tent before the city.
B001C033V019	1	33	19	And he bought a parcel of a field, where he had spread his tent, at the hand of the children of Hamor, Shechem's father, for a hundred pieces of money.
B001C033V020	1	33	20	And he erected there an altar, and called it Elelohe-israel.
B001C034V001	1	34	1	And Dinah the daughter of Leah, which she bore unto Jacob, went out to see the daughters of the land.
B001C034V002	1	34	2	And when Shechem the son of Hamor the Hivite, prince of the country, saw her, he took her, and lay with her, and defiled her.
B001C034V003	1	34	3	And his soul clung unto Dinah the daughter of Jacob, and he loved the damsel, and spoke kindly unto the damsel.
B001C034V004	1	34	4	And Shechem spoke unto his father Hamor, saying, Get me this damsel for my wife.
B001C034V005	1	34	5	And Jacob heard that he had defiled Dinah his daughter: now his sons were with his cattle in the field: and Jacob held his peace until they were come.
B001C034V006	1	34	6	And Hamor the father of Shechem went out unto Jacob to speak with him.
B001C034V007	1	34	7	And the sons of Jacob came out of the field when they heard it: and the men were grieved, and they were very angry, because he had wrought folly in Israel in lying with Jacob's daughter; which thing ought not to be done.
B001C034V008	1	34	8	And Hamor spoke with them, saying, The soul of my son Shechem longs for your daughter: I pray you give her to him for a wife.
B001C034V009	1	34	9	And make marriages with us, and give your daughters unto us, and take our daughters unto you.
B001C034V010	1	34	10	And you shall dwell with us: and the land shall be before you; dwell and trade in it, and get possessions in it.
B001C034V011	1	34	11	And Shechem said unto her father and unto her brethren, Let me find grace in your eyes, and what you shall say unto me I will give.
B001C034V012	1	34	12	Ask me ever so much dowry and gift, and I will give according as you shall say unto me: but give me the damsel for my wife.
B001C034V013	1	34	13	And the sons of Jacob answered Shechem and Hamor his father deceitfully, and said, because he had defiled Dinah their sister:
B001C034V014	1	34	14	And they said unto them, We cannot do this thing, to give our sister to one that is uncircumcised; for that would be a reproach unto us:
B001C034V015	1	34	15	But in this will we consent unto you: If you will be as we be, that every male of you be circumcised;
B001C034V016	1	34	16	Then will we give our daughters unto you, and we will take your daughters to us, and we will dwell with you, and we will become one people.
B001C034V017	1	34	17	But if you will not hearken unto us, to be circumcised; then will we take our daughter, and we will be gone.
B001C034V018	1	34	18	And their words pleased Hamor, and Shechem Hamor's son.
B001C034V019	1	34	19	And the young man deferred not to do the thing, because he had delight in Jacob's daughter: and he was more honorable than all the house of his father.
B001C034V020	1	34	20	And Hamor and Shechem his son came unto the gate of their city, and spoke with the men of their city, saying,
B001C034V021	1	34	21	These men are peaceable with us; therefore let them dwell in the land, and trade therein; for the land, behold, it is large enough for them; let us take their daughters to us for wives, and let us give them our daughters.
B001C034V022	1	34	22	Only in this will the men consent unto us for to dwell with us, to be one people, if every male among us be circumcised, as they are circumcised.
B001C034V023	1	34	23	Shall not their cattle and their substance and every beast of theirs be ours? only let us consent unto them, and they will dwell with us.
B001C034V024	1	34	24	And unto Hamor and unto Shechem his son hearkened all that went out of the gate of his city; and every male was circumcised, all that went out of the gate of his city.
B001C034V025	1	34	25	And it came to pass on the third day, when they were sore, that two of the sons of Jacob, Simeon and Levi, Dinah's brothers, took each man his sword, and came upon the city boldly, and slew all the males.
B001C034V026	1	34	26	And they slew Hamor and Shechem his son with the edge of the sword, and took Dinah out of Shechem's house, and went out.
B001C034V027	1	34	27	The sons of Jacob came upon the slain, and spoiled the city, because they had defiled their sister.
B001C034V028	1	34	28	They took their sheep, and their oxen, and their donkeys, and that which was in the city, and that which was in the field,
B001C034V029	1	34	29	And all their wealth, and all their little ones, and their wives took they captive, and spoiled even all that was in the house.
B001C034V030	1	34	30	And Jacob said to Simeon and Levi, You have troubled me to make me repulsive among the inhabitants of the land, among the Canaanites and the Perizzites: and I being few in number, they shall gather themselves together against me, and slay me; and I shall be destroyed, I and my house.
B001C034V031	1	34	31	And they said, Should he deal with our sister as with a harlot?
B001C035V001	1	35	1	And God said unto Jacob, 
B001C035V002	1	35	2	Then Jacob said unto his household, and to all that were with him, Put away the foreign gods that are among you, and be clean, and change your garments:
B001C035V003	1	35	3	And let us arise, and go up to Bethel; and I will make there an altar unto God, who answered me in the day of my distress, and was with me in the way which I went.
B001C035V004	1	35	4	And they gave unto Jacob all the foreign gods which were in their hand, and all their earrings which were in their ears; and Jacob hid them under the oak which was by Shechem.
B001C035V005	1	35	5	And they journeyed: and the terror of God was upon the cities that were round about them, and they did not pursue after the sons of Jacob.
B001C035V006	1	35	6	So Jacob came to Luz, which is in the land of Canaan, that is, Bethel, he and all the people that were with him.
B001C035V007	1	35	7	And he built there an altar, and called the place El-bethel: because there God appeared unto him, when he fled from the face of his brother.
B001C035V008	1	35	8	But Deborah Rebekah's nurse died, and she was buried beneath Bethel under an oak: and the name of it was called Allonbacuth.
B001C035V009	1	35	9	And God appeared unto Jacob again, when he came out of Paddanaram, and blessed him.
B001C035V010	1	35	10	And God said unto him, 
B001C035V011	1	35	11	And God said unto him, 
B001C035V012	1	35	12	
        
B001C035V013	1	35	13	And God went up from him in the place where he talked with him.
B001C035V014	1	35	14	And Jacob set up a pillar in the place where he talked with him, even a pillar of stone: and he poured a drink offering thereon, and he poured oil thereon.
B001C035V015	1	35	15	And Jacob called the name of the place where God spoke with him, Bethel.
B001C035V016	1	35	16	And they journeyed from Bethel; and there was but a little way to come to Ephrath: and Rachel travailed, and she had hard labor.
B001C035V017	1	35	17	And it came to pass, when she was in hard labor, that the midwife said unto her, Fear not; you shall have this son also.
B001C035V018	1	35	18	And it came to pass, as her soul was departing, (for she died) that she called his name Benoni: but his father called him Benjamin.
B001C035V019	1	35	19	And Rachel died, and was buried in the way to Ephrath, which is Bethlehem.
B001C035V020	1	35	20	And Jacob set a pillar upon her grave: that is the pillar of Rachel's grave unto this day.
B001C035V021	1	35	21	And Israel journeyed, and spread his tent beyond the tower of Eder.
B001C035V022	1	35	22	And it came to pass, when Israel dwelt in that land, that Reuben went and lay with Bilhah his father's concubine: and Israel heard it. Now the sons of Jacob were twelve:
B001C035V023	1	35	23	The sons of Leah; Reuben, Jacob's firstborn, and Simeon, and Levi, and Judah, and Issachar, and Zebulun:
B001C035V024	1	35	24	The sons of Rachel; Joseph, and Benjamin:
B001C035V025	1	35	25	And the sons of Bilhah, Rachel's handmaid; Dan, and Naphtali:
B001C035V026	1	35	26	And the sons of Zilpah, Leah's handmaid; Gad, and Asher: these are the sons of Jacob, who were born to him in Paddanaram.
B001C035V027	1	35	27	And Jacob came unto Isaac his father unto Mamre, unto the city of Arbah, which is Hebron, where Abraham and Isaac sojourned.
B001C035V028	1	35	28	And the days of Isaac were a hundred and fourscore years.
B001C035V029	1	35	29	And Isaac breathed his last, and died, and was gathered unto his people, being old and full of days: and his sons Esau and Jacob buried him.
B001C036V001	1	36	1	Now these are the generations of Esau, who is Edom.
B001C036V002	1	36	2	Esau took his wives of the daughters of Canaan; Adah the daughter of Elon the Hittite, and Oholibamah the daughter of Anah the daughter of Zibeon the Hivite;
B001C036V003	1	36	3	And Basemath Ishmael's daughter, sister of Nebaioth.
B001C036V004	1	36	4	And Adah bore to Esau Eliphaz; and Basemath bore Reuel;
B001C036V005	1	36	5	And Oholibamah bore Jeush, and Jalam, and Korah: these are the sons of Esau, who were born unto him in the land of Canaan.
B001C036V006	1	36	6	And Esau took his wives, and his sons, and his daughters, and all the persons of his house, and his cattle, and all his beasts, and all his substance, which he had got in the land of Canaan; and went into the country from the face of his brother Jacob.
B001C036V007	1	36	7	For their riches were more than that they might dwell together; and the land in which they were strangers could not bear them because of their cattle.
B001C036V008	1	36	8	Thus dwelt Esau in mount Seir: Esau is Edom.
B001C036V009	1	36	9	And these are the generations of Esau the father of the Edomites in mount Seir:
B001C036V010	1	36	10	These are the names of Esau's sons; Eliphaz the son of Adah the wife of Esau, Reuel the son of Basemath the wife of Esau.
B001C036V011	1	36	11	And the sons of Eliphaz were Teman, Omar, Zepho, and Gatam, and Kenaz.
B001C036V012	1	36	12	And Timna was concubine to Eliphaz Esau's son; and she bore to Eliphaz Amalek: these were the sons of Adah Esau's wife.
B001C036V013	1	36	13	And these are the sons of Reuel; Nahath, and Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah: these were the sons of Basemath Esau's wife.
B001C036V014	1	36	14	And these were the sons of Oholibamah, the daughter of Anah the daughter of Zibeon, Esau's wife: and she bore to Esau Jeush, and Jalam, and Korah.
B001C036V015	1	36	15	These were chiefs of the sons of Esau: the sons of Eliphaz the firstborn son of Esau; chief Teman, chief Omar, chief Zepho, chief Kenaz,
B001C036V016	1	36	16	Chief Korah, chief Gatam, and chief Amalek: these are the chiefs that came of Eliphaz in the land of Edom; these were the sons of Adah.
B001C036V017	1	36	17	And these are the sons of Reuel Esau's son; chief Nahath, chief Zerah, chief Shammah, chief Mizzah: these are the chiefs that came of Reuel in the land of Edom; these are the sons of Basemath Esau's wife.
B001C036V018	1	36	18	And these are the sons of Oholibamah Esau's wife; chief Jeush, chief Jalam, chief Korah: these were the chiefs that came of Oholibamah the daughter of Anah, Esau's wife.
B001C036V019	1	36	19	These are the sons of Esau, who is Edom, and these are their chiefs.
B001C036V020	1	36	20	These are the sons of Seir the Horite, who inhabited the land; Lotan, and Shobal, and Zibeon, and Anah,
B001C036V021	1	36	21	And Dishon, and Ezer, and Dishan: these are the chiefs of the Horites, the children of Seir in the land of Edom.
B001C036V022	1	36	22	And the children of Lotan were Hori and Hemam; and Lotan's sister was Timna.
B001C036V023	1	36	23	And the children of Shobal were these; Alvan, and Manahath, and Ebal, Shepho, and Onam.
B001C036V024	1	36	24	And these are the children of Zibeon; both Aiah, and Anah: this was that Anah that found the mules in the wilderness, as he fed the donkeys of Zibeon his father.
B001C036V025	1	36	25	And the children of Anah were these; Dishon, and Oholibamah the daughter of Anah.
B001C036V026	1	36	26	And these are the children of Dishon; Hemdan, and Eshban, and Ithran, and Cheran.
B001C036V027	1	36	27	The children of Ezer are these; Bilhan, and Zaavan, and Akan.
B001C036V028	1	36	28	The children of Dishan are these; Uz, and Aran.
B001C036V029	1	36	29	These are the chiefs that came of the Horites; chief Lotan, chief Shobal, chief Zibeon, chief Anah,
B001C036V030	1	36	30	Chief Dishon, chief Ezer, chief Dishan: these are the chiefs that came of Hori, among their chiefs in the land of Seir.
B001C036V031	1	36	31	And these are the kings that reigned in the land of Edom, before there reigned any king over the children of Israel.
B001C036V032	1	36	32	And Bela the son of Beor reigned in Edom: and the name of his city was Dinhabah.
B001C036V033	1	36	33	And Bela died, and Jobab the son of Zerah of Bozrah reigned in his stead.
B001C036V034	1	36	34	And Jobab died, and Husham of the land of Temani reigned in his stead.
B001C036V035	1	36	35	And Husham died, and Hadad the son of Bedad, who smote Midian in the field of Moab, reigned in his stead: and the name of his city was Avith.
B001C036V036	1	36	36	And Hadad died, and Samlah of Masrekah reigned in his stead.
B001C036V037	1	36	37	And Samlah died, and Shaul of Rehoboth by the river reigned in his stead.
B001C036V038	1	36	38	And Shaul died, and Baalhanan the son of Achbor reigned in his stead.
B001C036V039	1	36	39	And Baalhanan the son of Achbor died, and Hadar reigned in his stead: and the name of his city was Pau; and his wife's name was Mehetabel, the daughter of Matred, the daughter of Mezahab.
B001C036V040	1	36	40	And these are the names of the chiefs that came of Esau, according to their families, after their places, by their names; chief Timnah, chief Alvah, chief Jetheth,
B001C036V041	1	36	41	Chief Oholibamah, chief Elah, chief Pinon,
B001C036V042	1	36	42	Chief Kenaz, chief Teman, chief Mibzar,
B001C036V043	1	36	43	Chief Magdiel, chief Iram: these are the chiefs of Edom, according to their habitations in the land of their possession: he is Esau the father of the Edomites.
B001C037V001	1	37	1	And Jacob dwelt in the land in which his father was a stranger, in the land of Canaan.
B001C037V002	1	37	2	These are the generations of Jacob. Joseph, being seventeen years old, was feeding the flock with his brothers; and the lad was with the sons of Bilhah, and with the sons of Zilpah, his father's wives: and Joseph brought unto his father their evil report.
B001C037V003	1	37	3	Now Israel loved Joseph more than all his children, because he was the son of his old age: and he made him a coat of many colors.
B001C037V004	1	37	4	And when his brothers saw that their father loved him more than all his brothers, they hated him, and could not speak peaceably unto him.
B001C037V005	1	37	5	And Joseph dreamed a dream, and he told it to his brothers: and they hated him yet the more.
B001C037V006	1	37	6	And he said unto them, Hear, I pray you, this dream which I have dreamed:
B001C037V007	1	37	7	For, behold, we were binding sheaves in the field, and, lo, my sheaf arose, and also stood upright; and, behold, your sheaves stood round about, and bowed down to my sheaf.
B001C037V008	1	37	8	And his brothers said to him, Shall you indeed reign over us? or shall you indeed have dominion over us? And they hated him yet the more for his dreams, and for his words.
B001C037V009	1	37	9	And he dreamed yet another dream, and told it to his brothers, and said, Behold, I have dreamed another dream; and, behold, the sun and the moon and the eleven stars bowed down to me.
B001C037V010	1	37	10	And he told it to his father, and to his brothers: and his father rebuked him, and said unto him, What is this dream that you have dreamed? Shall I and your mother and your brothers indeed come to bow down ourselves to you to the earth?
B001C037V011	1	37	11	And his brothers envied him; but his father observed the saying.
B001C037V012	1	37	12	And his brothers went to feed their father's flock in Shechem.
B001C037V013	1	37	13	And Israel said unto Joseph, Do not your brothers feed the flock in Shechem? come, and I will send you unto them. And he said to him, Here am I.
B001C037V014	1	37	14	And he said to him, Go, I pray you, see whether it is well with your brothers, and well with the flocks; and bring me word again. So he sent him out of the valley of Hebron, and he came to Shechem.
B001C037V015	1	37	15	And a certain man found him, and, behold, he was wandering in the field: and the man asked him, saying, What seek you?
B001C037V016	1	37	16	And he said, I seek my brothers: tell me, I pray you, where they feed their flocks.
B001C037V017	1	37	17	And the man said, They are departed from here; for I heard them say, Let us go to Dothan. And Joseph went after his brothers, and found them in Dothan.
B001C037V018	1	37	18	And when they saw him afar off, even before he came near unto them, they conspired against him to slay him.
B001C037V019	1	37	19	And they said one to another, Behold, this dreamer comes.
B001C037V020	1	37	20	Come now therefore, and let us slay him, and cast him into some pit, and we will say, Some evil beast has devoured him: and we shall see what will become of his dreams.
B001C037V021	1	37	21	And Reuben heard it, and he delivered him out of their hands; and said, Let us not kill him.
B001C037V022	1	37	22	And Reuben said unto them, Shed no blood, but cast him into this pit that is in the wilderness, and lay no hand upon him; that he might rid him out of their hands, to deliver him to his father again.
B001C037V023	1	37	23	And it came to pass, when Joseph came unto his brothers, that they stripped Joseph out of his coat, his coat of many colors that was on him;
B001C037V024	1	37	24	And they took him, and cast him into a pit: and the pit was empty, there was no water in it.
B001C037V025	1	37	25	And they sat down to eat bread: and they lifted up their eyes and looked, and, behold, a company of Ishmaelites came from Gilead with their camels bearing spices and balm and myrrh, going to carry it down to Egypt.
B001C037V026	1	37	26	And Judah said unto his brothers, What profit is it if we slay our brother, and conceal his blood?
B001C037V027	1	37	27	Come, and let us sell him to the Ishmaelites, and let not our hand be upon him; for he is our brother and our flesh. And his brothers were content.
B001C037V028	1	37	28	Then there passed by Midianites, merchantmen; and they drew and lifted up Joseph out of the pit, and sold Joseph to the Ishmaelites for twenty pieces of silver: and they brought Joseph into Egypt.
B001C037V029	1	37	29	And Reuben returned unto the pit; and, behold, Joseph was not in the pit; and he tore his clothes.
B001C037V030	1	37	30	And he returned unto his brothers, and said, The child is not; and I, where shall I go?
B001C037V031	1	37	31	And they took Joseph's coat, and killed a kid of the goats, and dipped the coat in the blood;
B001C037V032	1	37	32	And they sent the coat of many colors, and they brought it to their father; and said, This have we found: see now whether it be your son's coat or not.
B001C037V033	1	37	33	And he recognized it, and said, It is my son's coat; an evil beast has devoured him; Joseph is without doubt torn in pieces.
B001C037V034	1	37	34	And Jacob tore his clothes, and put sackcloth upon his loins, and mourned for his son many days.
B001C037V035	1	37	35	And all his sons and all his daughters rose up to comfort him; but he refused to be comforted; and he said, I will go down into the grave unto my son mourning. Thus his father wept for him.
B001C037V036	1	37	36	And the Midianites sold him into Egypt unto Potiphar, an officer of Pharaoh's, and captain of the guard.
B001C038V001	1	38	1	And it came to pass at that time, that Judah went down from his brothers, and turned in to a certain Adullamite, whose name was Hirah.
B001C038V002	1	38	2	And Judah saw there a daughter of a certain Canaanite, whose name was Shua; and he took her, and went in unto her.
B001C038V003	1	38	3	And she conceived, and bore a son; and he called his name Er.
B001C038V004	1	38	4	And she conceived again, and bore a son; and she called his name Onan.
B001C038V005	1	38	5	And she yet again conceived, and bore a son; and called his name Shelah: and he was at Chezib, when she bore him.
B001C038V006	1	38	6	And Judah took a wife for Er his firstborn, whose name was Tamar.
B001C038V007	1	38	7	And Er, Judah's firstborn, was wicked in the sight of the LORD; and the LORD slew him.
B001C038V008	1	38	8	And Judah said unto Onan, Go in unto your brother's wife, and marry her, and raise up descendants to your brother.
B001C038V009	1	38	9	And Onan knew that the descendant would not be his; and it came to pass, when he went in unto his brother's wife, that he spilled it on the ground, lest that he should give a descendant to his brother.
B001C038V010	1	38	10	And the thing which he did displeased the LORD: therefore he slew him also.
B001C038V011	1	38	11	Then said Judah to Tamar his daughter-in-law, Remain a widow at your father's house, till Shelah my son is grown: for he said, Lest perhaps he die also, as his brothers did. And Tamar went and dwelt in her father's house.
B001C038V012	1	38	12	And in process of time the daughter of Shua Judah's wife died; and Judah was comforted, and went up unto his sheep shearers to Timnah, he and his friend Hirah the Adullamite.
B001C038V013	1	38	13	And it was told Tamar, saying, Behold your father-in-law goes up to Timnah to shear his sheep.
B001C038V014	1	38	14	And she put her widow's garments off from her, and covered herself with a veil, and wrapped herself, and sat in an open place, which is by the way to Timnah; for she saw that Shelah was grown, and she was not given unto him as wife.
B001C038V015	1	38	15	When Judah saw her, he thought her to be a harlot; because she had covered her face.
B001C038V016	1	38	16	And he turned unto her by the way, and said, Go to, I pray you, let me come in unto you; (for he knew not that she was his daughter-in-law.) And she said, What will you give me, that you may come in unto me?
B001C038V017	1	38	17	And he said, I will send you a kid from the flock. And she said, Will you give me a pledge, till you send it?
B001C038V018	1	38	18	And he said, What pledge shall I give you? And she said, Your signet, and your bracelets, and your staff that is in your hand. And he gave it to her, and came in unto her, and she conceived by him.
B001C038V019	1	38	19	And she arose, and went away, and laid by her veil from her, and put on the garments of her widowhood.
B001C038V020	1	38	20	And Judah sent the kid by the hand of his friend the Adullamite, to receive his pledge from the woman's hand: but he found her not.
B001C038V021	1	38	21	Then he asked the men of that place, saying, Where is the harlot, that was openly by the wayside? And they said, There was no harlot in this place.
B001C038V022	1	38	22	And he returned to Judah, and said, I cannot find her; and also the men of the place said, There was no harlot in this place.
B001C038V023	1	38	23	And Judah said, Let her keep it to her, lest we be shamed: behold, I sent this kid, and you have not found her.
B001C038V024	1	38	24	And it came to pass about three months after, that it was told Judah, saying, Tamar your daughter-in-law has played the harlot; and also, behold, she is with child by harlotry. And Judah said, Bring her forth, and let her be burnt.
B001C038V025	1	38	25	When she was brought forth, she sent to her father-in-law, saying, By the man, whose these are, am I with child: and she said, Discern, I pray you, whose are these, the signet, and bracelets, and staff.
B001C038V026	1	38	26	And Judah acknowledged them, and said, She has been more righteous than I; because I gave her not to Shelah my son. And he knew her again no more.
B001C038V027	1	38	27	And it came to pass in the time of her travail, that, behold, twins were in her womb.
B001C038V028	1	38	28	And it came to pass, when she travailed, that the one put out his hand: and the midwife took and bound upon his hand a scarlet thread, saying, This came out first.
B001C038V029	1	38	29	And it came to pass, as he drew back his hand, that, behold, his brother came out: and she said, How have you broken forth? this breach be upon you: therefore his name was called Perez.
B001C038V030	1	38	30	And afterward came out his brother, that had the scarlet thread upon his hand: and his name was called Zerah.
B001C039V001	1	39	1	And Joseph was brought down to Egypt; and Potiphar, an officer of Pharaoh, captain of the guard, an Egyptian, bought him of the hands of the Ishmaelites, who had brought him down there.
B001C039V002	1	39	2	And the LORD was with Joseph, and he was a prosperous man; and he was in the house of his master the Egyptian.
B001C039V003	1	39	3	And his master saw that the LORD was with him, and that the LORD made all that he did to prosper in his hand.
B001C039V004	1	39	4	And Joseph found grace in his sight, and he served him: and he made him overseer over his house, and all that he had he put into his hand.
B001C039V005	1	39	5	And it came to pass from the time that he had made him overseer in his house, and over all that he had, that the LORD blessed the Egyptian's house for Joseph's sake; and the blessing of the LORD was upon all that he had in the house, and in the field.
B001C039V006	1	39	6	And he left all that he had in Joseph's hand; and he knew not anything he had, except the food which he did eat. And Joseph was a handsome person, and well favored.
B001C039V007	1	39	7	And it came to pass after these things, that his master's wife cast her eyes upon Joseph; and she said, Lie with me.
B001C039V008	1	39	8	But he refused, and said unto his master's wife, Behold, my master knows not what is with me in the house, and he has committed all that he has to my hand;
B001C039V009	1	39	9	There is none greater in this house than I; neither has he kept back anything from me but you, because you are his wife: how then can I do this great wickedness, and sin against God?
B001C039V010	1	39	10	And it came to pass, as she spoke to Joseph day by day, that he hearkened not unto her, to lie by her, or to be with her.
B001C039V011	1	39	11	And it came to pass about this time, that Joseph went into the house to do his work; and there was none of the men of the house there within.
B001C039V012	1	39	12	And she caught him by his garment, saying, Lie with me: and he left his garment in her hand, and fled, and got out.
B001C039V013	1	39	13	And it came to pass, when she saw that he had left his garment in her hand, and was fled forth,
B001C039V014	1	39	14	That she called unto the men of her house, and spoke unto them, saying, See, he has brought in a Hebrew unto us to mock us; he came in unto me to lie with me, and I cried with a loud voice:
B001C039V015	1	39	15	And it came to pass, when he heard that I lifted up my voice and cried, that he left his garment with me, and fled, and got out.
B001C039V016	1	39	16	And she laid up his garment by her, until his lord came home.
B001C039V017	1	39	17	And she spoke unto him according to these words, saying, The Hebrew servant, which you have brought unto us, came in unto me to mock me:
B001C039V018	1	39	18	And it came to pass, as I lifted up my voice and cried, that he left his garment with me, and fled out.
B001C039V019	1	39	19	And it came to pass, when his master heard the words of his wife, which she spoke unto him, saying, After this manner did your servant to me; that his wrath was kindled.
B001C039V020	1	39	20	And Joseph's master took him, and put him into the prison, a place where the king's prisoners were bound: and he was there in the prison.
B001C039V021	1	39	21	But the LORD was with Joseph, and showed him mercy, and gave him favor in the sight of the keeper of the prison.
B001C039V022	1	39	22	And the keeper of the prison committed to Joseph's hand all the prisoners that were in the prison; and whatsoever they did there, he was the doer of it.
B001C039V023	1	39	23	The keeper of the prison looked not to anything that was under his hand; because the LORD was with him, and that which he did, the LORD made it to prosper.
B001C040V001	1	40	1	And it came to pass after these things, that the butler of the king of Egypt and his baker had offended their lord the king of Egypt.
B001C040V002	1	40	2	And Pharaoh was angry against two of his officers, against the chief of the butlers, and against the chief of the bakers.
B001C040V003	1	40	3	And he put them in custody in the house of the captain of the guard, into the prison, the place where Joseph was bound.
B001C040V004	1	40	4	And the captain of the guard charged Joseph with them, and he served them: and they continued    awhile in custody.
B001C040V005	1	40	5	And they dreamed a dream both of them, each man his dream in one night, each man according to the interpretation of his dream, the butler and the baker of the king of Egypt, who were bound in the prison.
B001C040V006	1	40	6	And Joseph came in unto them in the morning, and looked upon them, and, behold, they were sad.
B001C040V007	1	40	7	And he asked Pharaoh's officers that were with him in custody in his lord's house, saying, Why do you look so sad today?
B001C040V008	1	40	8	And they said unto him, We have dreamed a dream, and there is no interpreter of it. And Joseph said unto them, Do not interpretations belong to God? tell me them, I pray you.
B001C040V009	1	40	9	And the chief butler told his dream to Joseph, and said to him, In my dream, behold, a vine was before me;
B001C040V010	1	40	10	And in the vine were three branches: and it was as though it budded, and its blossoms shot forth; and the clusters thereof brought forth ripe grapes:
B001C040V011	1	40	11	And Pharaoh's cup was in my hand: and I took the grapes, and pressed them into Pharaoh's cup, and I gave the cup into Pharaoh's hand.
B001C040V012	1	40	12	And Joseph said unto him, This is the interpretation of it: The three branches are three days:
B001C040V013	1	40	13	Yet within three days shall Pharaoh lift up your head, and restore you unto your place: and you shall deliver Pharaoh's cup into his hand, after the former manner when you were his butler.
B001C040V014	1	40	14	But think of me when it shall be well with you, and show kindness, I pray you, unto me, and make mention of me unto Pharaoh, and bring me out of this house:
B001C040V015	1	40	15	For indeed I was stolen away out of the land of the Hebrews: and here also have I done nothing that they should put me into the dungeon.
B001C040V016	1	40	16	When the chief baker saw that the interpretation was good, he said unto Joseph, I also was in my dream, and, behold, I had three white baskets on my head:
B001C040V017	1	40	17	And in the uppermost basket there was all manner of baked food for Pharaoh; and the birds did eat them out of the basket upon my head.
B001C040V018	1	40	18	And Joseph answered and said, This is the interpretation thereof: The three baskets are three days:
B001C040V019	1	40	19	Yet within three days shall Pharaoh lift up your head from off you, and shall hang you on a tree; and the birds shall eat your flesh from off you.
B001C040V020	1	40	20	And it came to pass the third day, which was Pharaoh's birthday, that he made a feast unto all his servants: and he lifted up the head of the chief butler and of the chief baker among his servants.
B001C040V021	1	40	21	And he restored the chief butler unto his butlership again; and he gave the cup into Pharaoh's hand:
B001C040V022	1	40	22	But he hanged the chief baker: as Joseph had interpreted to them.
B001C040V023	1	40	23	Yet did not the chief butler remember Joseph, but forgot him.
B001C041V001	1	41	1	And it came to pass at the end of two full years, that Pharaoh dreamed: and, behold, he stood by the river.
B001C041V002	1	41	2	And, behold, there came up out of the river seven well favored cows and fat; and they fed in a meadow.
B001C041V003	1	41	3	And, behold, seven other cows came up after them out of the river, ill favored and thin; and stood by the other cows upon the bank of the river.
B001C041V004	1	41	4	And the ill favored and thin cows did eat up the seven well favored and fat cows. So Pharaoh awoke.
B001C041V005	1	41	5	And he slept and dreamed the second time: and, behold, seven ears of grain came up upon one stalk, full and good.
B001C041V006	1	41	6	And, behold, seven thin ears and dried by the east wind sprung up after them.
B001C041V007	1	41	7	And the seven thin ears devoured the seven healthy and full ears. And Pharaoh awoke, and, behold, it was a dream.
B001C041V008	1	41	8	And it came to pass in the morning that his spirit was troubled; and he sent and called for all the magicians of Egypt, and all the wise men thereof: and Pharaoh told them his dreams; but there was none that could interpret them unto Pharaoh.
B001C041V009	1	41	9	Then spoke the chief butler unto Pharaoh, saying, I do remember my faults this day:
B001C041V010	1	41	10	Pharaoh was angry with his servants, and put me in custody in the captain of the guard's house, both me and the chief baker:
B001C041V011	1	41	11	And we dreamed a dream in one night, I and he; we dreamed each man according to the interpretation of his dream.
B001C041V012	1	41	12	And there was there with us a young man, a Hebrew, servant to the captain of the guard; and we told him, and he interpreted to us our dreams; to each man according to his dream he did interpret.
B001C041V013	1	41	13	And it came to pass, as he interpreted to us, so it was; me he restored unto my office, and him he hanged.
B001C041V014	1	41	14	Then Pharaoh sent and called Joseph, and they brought him hastily out of the dungeon: and he shaved himself, and changed his clothes, and came in unto Pharaoh.
B001C041V015	1	41	15	And Pharaoh said unto Joseph, I have dreamed a dream, and there is none that can interpret it: and I have heard say of you, that you can understand a dream to interpret it.
B001C041V016	1	41	16	And Joseph answered Pharaoh, saying, It is not in me: God shall give Pharaoh an answer of peace.
B001C041V017	1	41	17	And Pharaoh said unto Joseph, In my dream, behold, I stood upon the bank of the river:
B001C041V018	1	41	18	And, behold, there came up out of the river seven cows, fat and well favored; and they fed in a meadow:
B001C041V019	1	41	19	And, behold, seven other cows came up after them, poor and very ill favored and thin, such as I never saw in all the land of Egypt for badness:
B001C041V020	1	41	20	And the thin and the ill favored cows did eat up the first seven fat cows:
B001C041V021	1	41	21	And when they had eaten them up, it could not be known that they had eaten them; but they were still ill favored, as at the beginning. So I awoke.
B001C041V022	1	41	22	And I saw in my dream, and, behold, seven ears came up on one stalk, full and good:
B001C041V023	1	41	23	And, behold, seven ears, withered, thin, and dried by the east wind, sprung up after them:
B001C041V024	1	41	24	And the thin ears devoured the seven good ears: and I told this unto the magicians; but there was none that could declare it to me.
B001C041V025	1	41	25	And Joseph said unto Pharaoh, The dream of Pharaoh is one: God has showed Pharaoh what he is about to do.
B001C041V026	1	41	26	The seven good cows are seven years; and the seven good ears are seven years: the dream is one.
B001C041V027	1	41	27	And the seven thin and ill favored cows that came up after them are seven years; and the seven empty ears dried by the east wind shall be seven years of famine.
B001C041V028	1	41	28	This is the thing which I have spoken unto Pharaoh: What God is about to do he shows unto Pharaoh.
B001C041V029	1	41	29	Behold, there comes seven years of great plenty throughout all the land of Egypt:
B001C041V030	1	41	30	And there shall arise after them seven years of famine; and all the plenty shall be forgotten in the land of Egypt; and the famine shall consume the land;
B001C041V031	1	41	31	And the plenty shall not be known in the land by reason of that famine following; for it shall be very grievous.
B001C041V032	1	41	32	And for that the dream was doubled unto Pharaoh twice; it is because the thing is established by God, and God will shortly bring it to pass.
B001C041V033	1	41	33	Now therefore let Pharaoh seek out a man discreet and wise, and set him over the land of Egypt.
B001C041V034	1	41	34	Let Pharaoh do this, and let him appoint officers over the land, and take up the fifth part of the land of Egypt in the seven plenteous years.
B001C041V035	1	41	35	And let them gather all the food of those good years that come, and lay up grain under the hand of Pharaoh, and let them keep food in the cities.
B001C041V036	1	41	36	And that food shall be for store to the land against the seven years of famine, which shall be in the land of Egypt; that the land perish not through the famine.
B001C041V037	1	41	37	And the thing was good in the eyes of Pharaoh, and in the eyes of all his servants.
B001C041V038	1	41	38	And Pharaoh said unto his servants, Can we find such a one as this is, a man in whom the Spirit of God is?
B001C041V039	1	41	39	And Pharaoh said unto Joseph, Since God has showed you all this, there is none so discreet and wise as you are:
B001C041V040	1	41	40	You shall be over my house, and according unto your word shall all my people be ruled: only in the throne will I be greater than you.
B001C041V041	1	41	41	And Pharaoh said unto Joseph, See, I have set you over all the land of Egypt.
B001C041V042	1	41	42	And Pharaoh took off his ring from his hand, and put it upon Joseph's hand, and arrayed him in clothing of fine linen, and put a gold chain about his neck;
B001C041V043	1	41	43	And he made him to ride in the second chariot which he had; and they cried before him, Bow the knee: and he made him ruler over all the land of Egypt.
B001C041V044	1	41	44	And Pharaoh said unto Joseph, I am Pharaoh, and without you shall no man lift up his hand or foot in all the land of Egypt.
B001C041V045	1	41	45	And Pharaoh called Joseph's name Zaphenathpaneah; and he gave him to wife Asenath the daughter of Potiphera priest of On. And Joseph went out over all the land of Egypt.
B001C041V046	1	41	46	And Joseph was thirty years old when he stood before Pharaoh king of Egypt. And Joseph went out from the presence of Pharaoh, and went throughout all the land of Egypt.
B001C041V047	1	41	47	And in the seven plenteous years the earth brought forth by handfuls.
B001C041V048	1	41	48	And he gathered up all the food of the seven years, which were in the land of Egypt, and laid up the food in the cities: the food of the field, which was round about every city, laid he up in the same.
B001C041V049	1	41	49	And Joseph gathered grain as the sand of the sea, very much, until he quit numbering; for it was without number.
B001C041V050	1	41	50	And unto Joseph were born two sons before the years of famine came, which Asenath the daughter of Potiphera priest of On bore unto him.
B001C041V051	1	41	51	And Joseph called the name of the firstborn Manasseh: For God, said he, has made me forget all my toil, and all my father's house.
B001C041V052	1	41	52	And the name of the second called he Ephraim: For God has caused me to be fruitful in the land of my affliction.
B001C041V053	1	41	53	And the seven years of plenty, that was in the land of Egypt, were ended.
B001C041V054	1	41	54	And the seven years of famine began to come, according as Joseph had said: and the famine was in all lands; but in all the land of Egypt there was bread.
B001C041V055	1	41	55	And when all the land of Egypt was famished, the people cried to Pharaoh for bread: and Pharaoh said unto all the Egyptians, Go unto Joseph; what he says to you, do.
B001C041V056	1	41	56	And the famine was over all the face of the earth: And Joseph opened all the storehouses, and sold unto the Egyptians; and the famine was severe in the land of Egypt.
B001C041V057	1	41	57	And all countries came into Egypt to Joseph to buy grain; because that the famine was so severe in all lands.
B001C042V001	1	42	1	Now when Jacob saw that there was grain in Egypt, Jacob said unto his sons, Why do you look one upon another?
B001C042V002	1	42	2	And he said, Behold, I have heard that there is grain in Egypt: get you down there, and buy for us from there; that we may live, and not die.
B001C042V003	1	42	3	And Joseph's ten brothers went down to buy grain in Egypt.
B001C042V004	1	42	4	But Benjamin, Joseph's brother, Jacob sent not with his brothers; for he said, Lest perhaps mischief befall him.
B001C042V005	1	42	5	And the sons of Israel came to buy grain among those that came: for the famine was in the land of Canaan.
B001C042V006	1	42	6	And Joseph was the governor over the land, and he it was that sold to all the people of the land: and Joseph's brothers came, and bowed down themselves before him with their faces to the earth.
B001C042V007	1	42	7	And Joseph saw his brothers, and he knew them, but made himself unknown unto them, and spoke roughly unto them; and he said unto them, from where do you come? And they said, From the land of Canaan to buy food.
B001C042V008	1	42	8	And Joseph knew his brothers, but they knew not him.
B001C042V009	1	42	9	And Joseph remembered the dreams which he dreamed of them, and said unto them, You are spies; to see the nakedness of the land you are come.
B001C042V010	1	42	10	And they said unto him, Nay, my lord, but to buy food are your servants come.
B001C042V011	1	42	11	We are all one man's sons; we are honest men, your servants are no spies.
B001C042V012	1	42	12	And he said unto them, Nay, but to see the nakedness of the land you are come.
B001C042V013	1	42	13	And they said, Your servants are twelve brothers, the sons of one man in the land of Canaan; and, behold, the youngest is this day with our father, and one is not.
B001C042V014	1	42	14	And Joseph said unto them, It is as I spoke unto you, saying, You are spies:
B001C042V015	1	42	15	Hereby you shall be proved: By the life of Pharaoh you shall not go forth from here, except your youngest brother come here.
B001C042V016	1	42	16	Send one of you, and let him fetch your brother, and you shall be kept in prison, that your words may be proved, whether there be any truth in you: or else by the life of Pharaoh surely you are spies.
B001C042V017	1	42	17	And he put them all together into custody three days.
B001C042V018	1	42	18	And Joseph said unto them the third day, This do, and live; for I fear God:
B001C042V019	1	42	19	If you be true men, let one of your brothers be bound in the house of your prison: go, carry grain for the famine of your houses:
B001C042V020	1	42	20	But bring your youngest brother unto me; so shall your words be verified, and you shall not die. And they did so.
B001C042V021	1	42	21	And they said one to another, We are verily guilty concerning our brother, in that we saw the anguish of his soul, when he besought us, and we would not hear; therefore is this distress come upon us.
B001C042V022	1	42	22	And Reuben answered them, saying, Spoke I not unto you, saying, Do not sin against the child; and you would not hear? therefore, behold, also his blood is required.
B001C042V023	1	42	23	And they knew not that Joseph understood them; for he spoke unto them by an interpreter.
B001C042V024	1	42	24	And he turned himself about from them, and wept; and returned to them again, and spoke with them, and took from them Simeon, and bound him before their eyes.
B001C042V025	1	42	25	Then Joseph commanded to fill their sacks with grain, and to restore every man's money into his sack, and to give them provision for the way: and thus did he unto them.
B001C042V026	1	42	26	And they loaded their donkeys with the grain, and departed there.
B001C042V027	1	42	27	And as one of them opened his sack to give his donkey provender in the inn, he saw his money; for, behold, it was in his sack's mouth.
B001C042V028	1	42	28	And he said unto his brothers, My money is restored; and, lo, it is even in my sack: and their hearts failed them, and they were afraid, saying one to another, What is this that God has done unto us?
B001C042V029	1	42	29	And they came unto Jacob their father unto the land of Canaan, and told him all that befell them; saying,
B001C042V030	1	42	30	The man, who is the lord of the land, spoke roughly to us, and took us for spies of the country.
B001C042V031	1	42	31	And we said unto him, We are honest men; we are no spies:
B001C042V032	1	42	32	We are twelve brothers, sons of our father; one is not, and the youngest is this day with our father in the land of Canaan.
B001C042V033	1	42	33	And the man, the lord of the country, said unto us, Hereby shall I know that you are honest men; leave one of your brothers here with me, and take food for the famine of your households, and be gone:
B001C042V034	1	42	34	And bring your youngest brother unto me: then shall I know that you are no spies, but that you are honest men: so will I deliver you your brother, and you shall trade in the land.
B001C042V035	1	42	35	And it came to pass as they emptied their sacks, that, behold, every man's bundle of money was in his sack: and when both they and their father saw the bundles of money, they were afraid.
B001C042V036	1	42	36	And Jacob their father said unto them, Me have you bereaved of my children: Joseph is not, and Simeon is not, and you will take Benjamin away: all these things are against me.
B001C042V037	1	42	37	And Reuben spoke unto his father, saying, Slay my two sons, if I bring him not to you: deliver him into my hand, and I will bring him to you again.
B001C042V038	1	42	38	And he said, My son shall not go down with you; for his brother is dead, and he is left alone: if mischief befall him by the way in which you go, then shall you bring down my gray hairs with sorrow to the grave.
B001C043V001	1	43	1	And the famine was severe in the land.
B001C043V002	1	43	2	And it came to pass, when they had eaten up the grain which they had brought out of Egypt, their father said unto them, Go again, buy us a little food.
B001C043V003	1	43	3	And Judah spoke unto him, saying, The man did solemnly warn unto us, saying, You shall not see my face, except your brother be with you.
B001C043V004	1	43	4	If you will send our brother with us, we will go down and buy you food:
B001C043V005	1	43	5	But if you will not send him, we will not go down: for the man said unto us, You shall not see my face, except your brother be with you.
B001C043V006	1	43	6	And Israel said, Why dealt you so ill with me, as to tell the man whether you had yet a brother?
B001C043V007	1	43	7	And they said, The man asked us carefully of our state, and of our kindred, saying, Is your father yet alive? have you another brother? and we told him according to the tenor of these words: could we in any way know that he would say, Bring your brother down?
B001C043V008	1	43	8	And Judah said unto Israel his father, Send the lad with me, and we will arise and go; that we may live, and not die, both we, and you, and also our little ones.
B001C043V009	1	43	9	I will be surety for him; of my hand shall you require him: if I bring him not unto you, and set him before you, then let me bear the blame forever:
B001C043V010	1	43	10	For except we had lingered, surely now we would have returned this second time.
B001C043V011	1	43	11	And their father Israel said unto them, If it must be so now, do this; take of the best fruits in the land in your vessels, and carry down the man a present, a little balm, and a little honey, spices, and myrrh, nuts, and almonds:
