B017C009V009	17	9	9	And Parmashta, and Arisai, and Aridai, and Vaizatha,
B017C009V010	17	9	10	The ten sons of Haman the son of Hammedatha, the enemy of the Jews, they killed; but on the spoil they laid not their hand.
B017C009V011	17	9	11	On that day the number of those that were slain in Shushan the citadel was brought before the king.
B017C009V012	17	9	12	And the king said unto Esther the queen, The Jews have slain and destroyed five hundred men in Shushan the citadel, and the ten sons of Haman; what have they done in the rest of the king's provinces? now what is your petition? and it shall be granted you: or what is your request further? and it shall be done.
B017C009V013	17	9	13	Then said Esther, If it please the king, let it be granted to the Jews who are in Shushan to do tomorrow also according unto this day's decree, and let Haman's ten sons be hanged upon the gallows.
B017C009V014	17	9	14	And the king commanded it so to be done: and the decree was given at Shushan; and they hanged Haman's ten sons.
B017C009V015	17	9	15	For the Jews that were in Shushan gathered themselves together on the fourteenth day also of the month Adar, and killed three hundred men at Shushan; but on the spoil they laid not their hand.
B017C009V016	17	9	16	But the other Jews that were in the king's provinces gathered themselves together, and defended their lives, and had rest from their enemies, and killed of their foes seventy and five thousand, but they laid not their hands on the spoil,
B017C009V017	17	9	17	On the thirteenth day of the month Adar; and on the fourteenth day of the same they rested, and made it a day of feasting and gladness.
B017C009V018	17	9	18	But the Jews that were at Shushan assembled together on the thirteenth day thereof, and on the fourteenth thereof; and on the fifteenth day of the same they rested, and made it a day of feasting and gladness.
B017C009V019	17	9	19	Therefore the Jews of the villages, that dwelt in the unwalled towns, made the fourteenth day of the month Adar a day of gladness and feasting, and a good day, and of sending presents one to another.
B017C009V020	17	9	20	And Mordecai wrote these things, and sent letters unto all the Jews that were in all the provinces of king Ahasuerus, both near and far,
B017C009V021	17	9	21	To establish this among them, that they should keep the fourteenth day of the month Adar, and the fifteenth day of the same, yearly,
B017C009V022	17	9	22	As the days on which the Jews rested from their enemies, and the month which was turned unto them from sorrow to joy, and from mourning into a good day: that they should make them days of feast
B017C009V023	17	9	23	And the Jews undertook to do as they had begun, and as Mordecai had written unto them;
B017C009V024	17	9	24	Because Haman the son of Hammedatha, the Agagite, the enemy of all the Jews, had plotted against the Jews to destroy them, and had cast Pur, that is, the lot, to consume them, and to destroy them;
B017C009V025	17	9	25	But when Esther came before the king, he commanded by letters that his wicked plot, which he devised against the Jews, should return upon his own head, and that he and his sons should be hanged on the gallows.
B017C009V026	17	9	26	Therefore they called these days Purim after the name of Pur. Therefore for all the words of this letter, and of that which they had seen concerning this matter, and which had come unto them,
B017C009V027	17	9	27	The Jews ordained, and took upon themselves, and upon their descendants, and upon all such as joined themselves unto them, so that it should not fail, that they would keep these two days according to what was written, and according to their appointed time every year;
B017C009V028	17	9	28	And that these days should be remembered and kept throughout every generation, every family, every province, and every city; and that these days of Purim should not fall into disuse among the Jews, nor the memory of them perish from their descendants.
B017C009V029	17	9	29	Then Esther the queen, the daughter of Abihail, and Mordecai the Jew, wrote with all authority, to confirm this second letter about Purim.
B017C009V030	17	9	30	And he sent the letters unto all the Jews, to the hundred twenty and seven provinces of the kingdom of Ahasuerus, with words of peace and truth,
B017C009V031	17	9	31	To confirm these days of Purim in their times appointed, according as Mordecai the Jew and Esther the queen had enjoined them, and as they had decreed for themselves and for their descendants, concerning the matters of the fastings and their lamentations.
B017C009V032	17	9	32	And the decree of Esther confirmed these matters of Purim; and it was written in the book.
B017C010V001	17	10	1	And king Ahasuerus imposed tribute upon the land, and upon the coastlands of the sea.
B017C010V002	17	10	2	And all the acts of his power and of his might, and the declaration of the greatness of Mordecai, to which the king advanced him, are they not written in the book of the chronicles of the kings of Media and Persia?
B017C010V003	17	10	3	For Mordecai the Jew was next unto king Ahasuerus, and great among the Jews, and accepted by the multitude of his brethren, seeking the welfare of his people, and speaking peace to all his countrymen.
B018C001V001	18	1	1	There was a man in the land of Uz, whose name was Job; and that man was blameless and upright, and one that feared God, and turned away from evil.
B018C001V002	18	1	2	And there were born unto him seven sons and three daughters.
B018C001V003	18	1	3	His possessions also were seven thousand sheep, and three thousand camels, and five hundred yoke of oxen, and five hundred female donkeys, and a very great household; so that this man was the greatest of all the men of the east.
B018C001V004	18	1	4	And his sons went and feasted in their houses, every one on his day; and sent and called for their three sisters to eat and to drink with them.
B018C001V005	18	1	5	And it was so, when the days of their feasting were finished, that Job sent and sanctified them, and rose up early in the morning, and offered burnt offerings according to the number of them all: for Job said, It may be that my sons have sinned, and cursed God in their hearts. Thus did Job continually.
B018C001V006	18	1	6	Now there was a day when the sons of God came to present themselves before the LORD, and Satan came also among them.
B018C001V007	18	1	7	And the LORD said unto Satan, 
B018C001V008	18	1	8	And the LORD said unto Satan, 
B018C001V009	18	1	9	Then Satan answered the LORD, and said, Does Job fear God for nothing?
B018C001V010	18	1	10	Have not you made a hedge about him, and about his house, and about all that he has on every side? you have blessed the work of his hands, and his possessions are increased in the land.
B018C001V011	18	1	11	But put forth your hand now, and touch all that he has, and he will curse you to your face.
B018C001V012	18	1	12	And the LORD said unto Satan, 
B018C001V013	18	1	13	And there was a day when his sons and his daughters were eating and drinking wine in their eldest brotherâ€™s house:
B018C001V014	18	1	14	And there came a messenger unto Job, and said, The oxen were plowing, and the donkeys feeding beside them:
B018C001V015	18	1	15	And the Sabeans fell upon them, and took them away; yea, they have slain the servants with the edge of the sword; and I alone am escaped to tell you.
B018C001V016	18	1	16	While he was yet speaking, there came also another, and said, The fire of God has fallen from heaven, and has burned up the sheep, and the servants, and consumed them; and I alone am escaped to tell you.
B018C001V017	18	1	17	While he was yet speaking, there came also another, and said, The Chaldeans made out three bands, and fell upon the camels, and have carried them away, yea, and slain the servants with the edge of the sword; and I alone am escaped to tell you.
B018C001V018	18	1	18	While he was yet speaking, there came also another, and said, Your sons and your daughters were eating and drinking wine in their eldest brotherâ€™s house:
B018C001V019	18	1	19	And, behold, there came a great wind from the wilderness, and struck the four corners of the house, and it fell upon the young men, and they are dead; and I alone am escaped to tell you.
B018C001V020	18	1	20	Then Job arose, and tore his mantle, and shaved his head, and fell down upon the ground, and worshiped,
B018C001V021	18	1	21	And said, Naked came I out of my motherâ€™s womb, and naked shall I return there: the LORD gave, and the LORD has taken away; blessed be the name of the LORD.
B018C001V022	18	1	22	In all this Job sinned not, nor charged God with wrong.
B018C002V001	18	2	1	Again there was a day when the sons of God came to present themselves before the LORD, and Satan came also among them to present himself before the LORD.
B018C002V002	18	2	2	And the LORD said unto Satan, 
B018C002V003	18	2	3	And the LORD said unto Satan, 
B018C002V004	18	2	4	And Satan answered the LORD, and said, Skin for skin, yea, all that a man has will he give for his life.
B018C002V005	18	2	5	But put forth your hand now, and touch his bone and his flesh, and he will curse you to your face.
B018C002V006	18	2	6	And the LORD said unto Satan, 
B018C002V007	18	2	7	So went Satan forth from the presence of the LORD, and struck Job with painful boils from the sole of his foot unto the crown of his head.
B018C002V008	18	2	8	And he took himself a potsherd to scrape himself with; and he sat down among the ashes.
B018C002V009	18	2	9	Then said his wife unto him, Do you still retain your integrity? curse God, and die.
B018C002V010	18	2	10	But he said unto her, You speak as one of the foolish women speaks. What? shall we receive good at the hand of God, and shall we not receive evil? In all this did not Job sin with his lips.
B018C002V011	18	2	11	Now when Jobâ€™s three friends heard of all this evil that was come upon him, they came every one from his own place; Eliphaz the Temanite, and Bildad the Shuhite, and Zophar the Naamathite: for they had made an appointment together to come to mourn with him and to comfort him.
B018C002V012	18	2	12	And when they lifted up their eyes afar off, and knew him not, they lifted up their voice, and wept; and they tore every one his mantle, and sprinkled dust upon their heads toward heaven.
B018C002V013	18	2	13	So they sat down with him upon the ground seven days and seven nights, and none spoke a word unto him: for they saw that his grief was very great.
B018C003V001	18	3	1	After this opened Job his mouth, and cursed his day.
B018C003V002	18	3	2	And Job spoke, and said,
B018C003V003	18	3	3	Let the day perish on which I was born, and the night in which it was said, There is a male child conceived.
B018C003V004	18	3	4	Let that day be darkness; let not God regard it from above, neither let the light shine upon it.
B018C003V005	18	3	5	Let darkness and the shadow of death stain it; let a cloud dwell upon it; let the blackness of the day terrify it.
B018C003V006	18	3	6	As for that night, let darkness seize upon it; let it not rejoice among the days of the year, let it not come into the number of the months.
B018C003V007	18	3	7	Lo, let that night be solitary, let no joyful voice come into it.
B018C003V008	18	3	8	Let them curse it that curse the day, who are ready to arouse leviathan.
B018C003V009	18	3	9	Let the stars of its twilight be dark; let it look for light, but have none; neither let it see the dawning of the day:
B018C003V010	18	3	10	Because it shut not up the doors of my motherâ€™s womb, nor hid sorrow from my eyes.
B018C003V011	18	3	11	Why died I not from the womb? why did I not expire when I came out of the womb?
B018C003V012	18	3	12	Why did the knees receive me? or why the breasts that I should nurse?
B018C003V013	18	3	13	For now should I have lain still and been quiet, I should have slept: then would I have been at rest,
B018C003V014	18	3	14	With kings and counselors of the earth, who built desolate places for themselves;
B018C003V015	18	3	15	Or with princes that had gold, who filled their houses with silver:
B018C003V016	18	3	16	Or as a hidden untimely birth, I had not been; as infants who never saw light.
B018C003V017	18	3	17	There the wicked cease from troubling; and there the weary are at rest.
B018C003V018	18	3	18	There the prisoners rest together; they hear not the voice of the oppressor.
B018C003V019	18	3	19	The small and great are there; and the servant is free from his master.
B018C003V020	18	3	20	Therefore is light given to him that is in misery, and life unto the bitter in soul;
B018C003V021	18	3	21	Who long for death, but it comes not; and dig for it more than for hidden treasures;
B018C003V022	18	3	22	Who rejoice exceedingly, and are glad, when they can find the grave?
B018C003V023	18	3	23	Why is light given to a man whose way is hid, and whom God has hedged in?
B018C003V024	18	3	24	For my sighing comes before I eat, and my groanings are poured out like the waters.
B018C003V025	18	3	25	For the thing which I greatly feared has come upon me, and that which I was afraid of has come unto me.
B018C003V026	18	3	26	I was not at ease, neither had I quiet, neither was I at rest; yet trouble came.
B018C004V001	18	4	1	Then Eliphaz the Temanite answered and said,
B018C004V002	18	4	2	If we venture to converse with you, will you be grieved? but who can withhold himself from speaking?
B018C004V003	18	4	3	Behold, you have instructed many, and you have strengthened the weak hands.
B018C004V004	18	4	4	Your words have upheld him that was falling, and you have strengthened the feeble knees.
B018C004V005	18	4	5	But now it is come upon you, and you faint; it touches you, and you are troubled.
B018C004V006	18	4	6	Is not this your fear, your confidence, your hope, and the uprightness of your ways?
B018C004V007	18	4	7	Remember, I pray you, who ever perished, being innocent? or where were the righteous cut off?
B018C004V008	18	4	8	Even as I have seen, they that plow iniquity, and sow wickedness, reap the same.
B018C004V009	18	4	9	By the blast of God they perish, and by the breath of his nostrils are they consumed.
B018C004V010	18	4	10	The roaring of the lion, and the voice of the fierce lion, and the teeth of the young lions, are broken.
B018C004V011	18	4	11	The old lion perishes for lack of prey, and the strong lionâ€™s whelps are scattered abroad.
B018C004V012	18	4	12	Now a thing was secretly brought to me, and my ear received a whisper of it.
B018C004V013	18	4	13	In thoughts from the visions of the night, when deep sleep falls on men,
B018C004V014	18	4	14	Fear came upon me, and trembling, which made all my bones to shake.
B018C004V015	18	4	15	Then a spirit passed before my face; the hair of my flesh stood up:
B018C004V016	18	4	16	It stood still, but I could not discern its form: an image was before my eyes, there was silence, and I heard a voice, saying,
B018C004V017	18	4	17	Shall mortal man be more just than God? shall a man be more pure than his maker?
B018C004V018	18	4	18	Behold, he put no trust in his servants; and his angels he charged with folly:
B018C004V019	18	4	19	How much less in them that dwell in houses of clay, whose foundation is in the dust, who are crushed before the moth?
B018C004V020	18	4	20	They are destroyed from morning to evening: they perish forever without any regarding it.
B018C004V021	18	4	21	Does not their excellence which is in them go away? they die, even without wisdom.
B018C005V001	18	5	1	Call now, if there be any that will answer you; and to which of the holy ones will you turn?
B018C005V002	18	5	2	For wrath kills the foolish man, and envy slays the simple one.
B018C005V003	18	5	3	I have seen the foolish taking root: but suddenly I cursed his habitation.
B018C005V004	18	5	4	His children are far from safety, and they are crushed in the gate, neither is there any to deliver them.
B018C005V005	18	5	5	Whose harvest the hungry eats up, and takes it even out of the thorns, and the robber swallows up their wealth.
B018C005V006	18	5	6	For affliction comes not forth from the dust, neither does trouble spring out of the ground;
B018C005V007	18	5	7	Yet man is born unto trouble, as the sparks fly upward.
B018C005V008	18	5	8	I would seek unto God, and unto God would I commit my cause:
B018C005V009	18	5	9	Who does great things and unsearchable; marvelous things without number:
B018C005V010	18	5	10	Who gives rain upon the earth, and sends waters upon the fields:
B018C005V011	18	5	11	To set up on high those that are low; that those who mourn may be lifted to safety.
B018C005V012	18	5	12	He frustrates the devices of the crafty, so that their hands cannot perform their plans.
B018C005V013	18	5	13	He takes the wise in their own craftiness: and the counsel of the cunning is quickly ended.
B018C005V014	18	5	14	They meet with darkness in the daytime, and grope in the noonday as in the night.
B018C005V015	18	5	15	But he saves the poor from the sword, from their mouth, and from the hand of the mighty.
B018C005V016	18	5	16	So the poor has hope, and injustice shuts her mouth.
B018C005V017	18	5	17	Behold, happy is the man whom God corrects: therefore despise not the chastening of the Almighty:
B018C005V018	18	5	18	For he bruises, and binds up: he wounds, and his hands make whole.
B018C005V019	18	5	19	He shall deliver you in six troubles: yea, in seven there shall no evil touch you.
B018C005V020	18	5	20	In famine he shall redeem you from death: and in war from the power of the sword.
B018C005V021	18	5	21	You shall be hid from the scourge of the tongue: neither shall you be afraid of destruction when it comes.
B018C005V022	18	5	22	At destruction and famine you shall laugh: neither shall you be afraid of the beasts of the earth.
B018C005V023	18	5	23	For you shall be in covenant with the stones of the field: and the beasts of the field shall be at peace with you.
B018C005V024	18	5	24	And you shall know that your tabernacle shall be in peace; and you shall visit your habitation, and shall find nothing amiss.
B018C005V025	18	5	25	You shall know also that your descendants shall be many, and your offspring as the grass of the earth.
B018C005V026	18	5	26	You shall come to your grave in a full age, like a shock of grain comes in in its season.
B018C005V027	18	5	27	Lo this, we have searched it out, so it is; hear it, and know you it for your good.
B018C006V001	18	6	1	But Job answered and said,
B018C006V002	18	6	2	Oh that my grief were thoroughly weighed, and my calamity laid in the balances together!
B018C006V003	18	6	3	For now it would be heavier than the sand of the sea: therefore my words are swallowed up.
B018C006V004	18	6	4	For the arrows of the Almighty are within me, the poison thereof drinks up my spirit: the terrors of God do set themselves in array against me.
B018C006V005	18	6	5	Does the wild donkey bray when it has grass? or the ox lows over its fodder?
B018C006V006	18	6	6	Can that which is tasteless be eaten without salt? or is there any taste in the white of an egg?
B018C006V007	18	6	7	The things that my soul refused to touch are as loathsome food to me.
B018C006V008	18	6	8	Oh that I might have my request; and that God would grant me the thing that I long for!
B018C006V009	18	6	9	Even that it would please God to destroy me; that he would let loose his hand, and cut me off!
B018C006V010	18	6	10	Then should I still have comfort; yea, I would exult myself in sorrow: let him not spare; for I have not concealed the words of the Holy One.
B018C006V011	18	6	11	What is my strength, that I should hope? and what is my end, that I should prolong my life?
B018C006V012	18	6	12	Is my strength the strength of stones? or is my flesh of bronze?
B018C006V013	18	6	13	Is not my help within me? and is wisdom driven quite from me?
B018C006V014	18	6	14	To him that is afflicted pity should be shown from his friend; even though he forsakes the fear of the Almighty.
B018C006V015	18	6	15	My brethren have dealt deceitfully as a brook, and as the stream of brooks that pass away;
B018C006V016	18	6	16	Which are black by reason of the ice, and in which the snow is hid:
B018C006V017	18	6	17	At what time they become warm, they vanish: when it is hot, they vanish out of their place.
B018C006V018	18	6	18	The paths of their way turn aside; they go nowhere, and perish.
B018C006V019	18	6	19	The caravans of Tema looked, the travelers of Sheba waited for them.
B018C006V020	18	6	20	They were disappointed because they had confidence; they came there, and were confused.
B018C006V021	18	6	21	For now you are nothing; you see my terror, and are afraid.
B018C006V022	18	6	22	Did I say, Bring unto me? or, Give a reward for me of your substance?
B018C006V023	18	6	23	Or, Deliver me from the enemyâ€™s hand? or, Redeem me from the hand of the mighty?
B018C006V024	18	6	24	Teach me, and I will hold my tongue: and cause me to understand how I have erred.
B018C006V025	18	6	25	How forceful are right words! but what does your arguing prove?
B018C006V026	18	6	26	Do you intend to reprove words, and the speeches of one that is desperate, which are as wind?
B018C006V027	18	6	27	Yea, you overwhelm the fatherless, and you dig a pit for your friend.
B018C006V028	18	6	28	Now therefore be content, look upon me; for it is evident unto you if I lie.
B018C006V029	18	6	29	Return, I pray you, let it not be injustice; yea, return again, my righteousness is in it.
B018C006V030	18	6	30	Is there iniquity in my tongue? cannot my taste discern perverse things?
B018C007V001	18	7	1	Is there not an appointed time to man upon earth? are not his days also like the days of a hireling?
B018C007V002	18	7	2	As a servant earnestly desires the shadow, and as a hireling looks for the reward of his work:
B018C007V003	18	7	3	So am I made to possess months of vanity, and wearisome nights are appointed to me.
B018C007V004	18	7	4	When I lie down, I say, When shall I arise, and the night be gone? and I am full of tossings to and fro unto the dawning of the day.
B018C007V005	18	7	5	My flesh is clothed with worms and clods of dust; my skin is broken, and become loathsome.
B018C007V006	18	7	6	My days are swifter than a weaverâ€™s shuttle, and are spent without hope.
B018C007V007	18	7	7	O remember that my life is a breath: my eye shall no more see good.
B018C007V008	18	7	8	The eye of him that has seen me shall see me no more: your eyes are upon me, and I am not.
B018C007V009	18	7	9	As the cloud is consumed and vanishes away: so he that goes down to the grave shall come up no more.
B018C007V010	18	7	10	He shall return no more to his house, neither shall his place know him any more.
B018C007V011	18	7	11	Therefore I will not restrain my mouth; I will speak in the anguish of my spirit; I will complain in the bitterness of my soul.
B018C007V012	18	7	12	Am I a sea, or a sea monster, that you set a watch over me?
B018C007V013	18	7	13	When I say, My bed shall comfort me, my couch shall ease my complaint;
B018C007V014	18	7	14	Then you scare me with dreams, and terrify me through visions:
B018C007V015	18	7	15	So that my soul chooses strangling, and death rather than my life.
B018C007V016	18	7	16	I loathe it; I would not live always: let me alone; for my days are vanity.
B018C007V017	18	7	17	What is man, that you should magnify him? and that you should set your heart upon him?
B018C007V018	18	7	18	And that you should visit him every morning, and test him every moment?
B018C007V019	18	7	19	How long will you not look away from me, nor let me alone till I swallow down my spittle?
B018C007V020	18	7	20	I have sinned; what shall I do unto you, O you preserver of men? why have you set me as a mark against you, so that I am a burden to myself?
B018C007V021	18	7	21	And why do you not pardon my transgression, and take away my iniquity? for now shall I sleep in the dust; and you shall seek me in the morning, but I shall not be.
B018C008V001	18	8	1	Then answered Bildad the Shuhite, and said,
B018C008V002	18	8	2	How long will you speak these things? and how long shall the words of your mouth be like a strong wind?
B018C008V003	18	8	3	Does God pervert judgment? or does the Almighty pervert justice?
B018C008V004	18	8	4	If your children have sinned against him, and he has cast them away for their transgression;
B018C008V005	18	8	5	If you would seek unto God early, and make your supplication to the Almighty;
B018C008V006	18	8	6	If you were pure and upright; surely now he would awake for you, and make the habitation of your righteousness prosperous.
B018C008V007	18	8	7	Though your beginning was small, yet your latter end should greatly increase.
B018C008V008	18	8	8	For inquire, I pray you, of the former age, and prepare yourself to the findings of their fathers:
B018C008V009	18	8	9	(For we are but of yesterday, and know nothing, because our days upon earth are a shadow:)
B018C008V010	18	8	10	Shall not they teach you, and tell you, and utter words out of their heart?
B018C008V011	18	8	11	Can the papyrus grow up without a marsh? can the reeds grow without water?
B018C008V012	18	8	12	While it is yet green, and not cut down, it withers before any other plant.
B018C008V013	18	8	13	So are the paths of all that forget God; and the hypocriteâ€™s hope shall perish:
B018C008V014	18	8	14	Whose confidence shall be cut off, and whose trust shall be a spiderâ€™s web.
B018C008V015	18	8	15	He shall lean upon his house, but it shall not stand: he shall hold it fast, but it shall not endure.
B018C008V016	18	8	16	He grows green in the sun, and his branch shoots forth in his garden.
B018C008V017	18	8	17	His roots are wrapped about the stone heap, and looks for a place in the stones.
B018C008V018	18	8	18	If he is destroyed from his place, then it will deny him, saying, I have not seen you.
B018C008V019	18	8	19	Behold, this is the joy of his way, and out of the earth shall others grow.
B018C008V020	18	8	20	Behold, God will not cast away a blameless man, neither will he help the evil doers:
B018C008V021	18	8	21	Till he fills your mouth with laughing, and your lips with rejoicing.
B018C008V022	18	8	22	They that hate you shall be clothed with shame; and the dwelling place of the wicked will come to nothing.
B018C009V001	18	9	1	Then Job answered and said,
B018C009V002	18	9	2	I know it is so of a truth: but how should man be just before God?
B018C009V003	18	9	3	If he will contend with him, he cannot answer him one of a thousand.
B018C009V004	18	9	4	He is wise in heart, and mighty in strength: who has hardened himself against him, and has prospered?
B018C009V005	18	9	5	Who removes the mountains, and they know not: who overturns them in his anger.
B018C009V006	18	9	6	Who shakes the earth out of its place, and the pillars thereof tremble.
B018C009V007	18	9	7	Who commands the sun, and it rises not; and seals up the stars.
B018C009V008	18	9	8	Who alone spreads out the heavens, and treads upon the waves of the sea.
B018C009V009	18	9	9	Who makes the Bear, Orion, and Pleiades, and the chambers of the south.
B018C009V010	18	9	10	Who does great things past finding out; yea, and wonders without number.
B018C009V011	18	9	11	Lo, he goes by me, and I see him not: he passes on also, but I perceive him not.
B018C009V012	18	9	12	Behold, he takes away, who can hinder him? who will say unto him, What do you?
B018C009V013	18	9	13	If God will not withdraw his anger, the proud helpers do bow before him.
B018C009V014	18	9	14	How much less shall I answer him, and choose out my words to reason with him?
B018C009V015	18	9	15	For, though I were righteous, yet could I not answer, but I would make supplication to my judge.
B018C009V016	18	9	16	If I had called, and he had answered me; yet would I not believe that he had hearkened unto my voice.
B018C009V017	18	9	17	For he breaks me with a tempest, and multiplies my wounds without cause.
B018C009V018	18	9	18	He will not permit me to take my breath, but fills me with bitterness.
B018C009V019	18	9	19	If I speak of strength, lo, he is strong: and if of justice, who shall set me a time to plead?
B018C009V020	18	9	20	If I justify myself, my own mouth shall condemn me: if I say, I am blameless, it shall also prove me perverse.
B018C009V021	18	9	21	Though I were blameless, yet would I not know my soul: I would despise my life.
B018C009V022	18	9	22	This is one thing, therefore I said it, He destroys the blameless and the wicked.
B018C009V023	18	9	23	If the scourge slays suddenly, he will laugh at the plight of the innocent.
B018C009V024	18	9	24	The earth is given into the hand of the wicked: he covers the faces of its judges; if not he, who then is it?
B018C009V025	18	9	25	Now my days are swifter than a runner: they flee away, they see no good.
B018C009V026	18	9	26	They are passed away as the swift ships: as the eagle that hastens to the prey.
B018C009V027	18	9	27	If I say, I will forget my complaint, I will leave off my heaviness, and comfort myself:
B018C009V028	18	9	28	I am afraid of all my sorrows, I know that you will not hold me innocent.
B018C009V029	18	9	29	If I am wicked, why then labor I in vain?
B018C009V030	18	9	30	If I wash myself with snow water, and make my hands ever so clean;
B018C009V031	18	9	31	Yet shall you plunge me in the ditch, and my own clothes shall abhor me.
B018C009V032	18	9	32	For he is not a man, as I am, that I should answer him, and we should come together in trial.
B018C009V033	18	9	33	Neither is there any mediator between us, that might lay his hand upon us both.
B018C009V034	18	9	34	Let him take his rod away from me, and let not his fear terrify me:
B018C009V035	18	9	35	Then would I speak, and not fear him; but it is not so with me.
B018C010V001	18	10	1	My soul is weary of my life; I will leave my complaint upon myself; I will speak in the bitterness of my soul.
B018C010V002	18	10	2	I will say unto God, Do not condemn me; show me why you contend with me.
B018C010V003	18	10	3	Is it good unto you that you should oppress, that you should despise the work of your hands, and smile upon the counsel of the wicked?
B018C010V004	18	10	4	Have you eyes of flesh? or see you as man sees?
B018C010V005	18	10	5	Are your days as the days of man? are your years as manâ€™s days,
B018C010V006	18	10	6	That you inquire after my iniquity, and search after my sin?
B018C010V007	18	10	7	You know that I am not wicked; and there is none that can deliver out of your hand.
B018C010V008	18	10	8	Your hands have made me and fashioned me together totally; yet you do destroy me.
B018C010V009	18	10	9	Remember, I beseech you, that you have made me as the clay; and will you bring me into dust again?
B018C010V010	18	10	10	Have you not poured me out as milk, and curdled me like cheese?
B018C010V011	18	10	11	You have clothed me with skin and flesh, and have knit me together with bones and sinews.
B018C010V012	18	10	12	You have granted me life and favor, and your care has preserved my spirit.
B018C010V013	18	10	13	And these things have you hid in your heart: I know that this is with you.
B018C010V014	18	10	14	If I sin, then you mark me, and you will not acquit me from my iniquity.
B018C010V015	18	10	15	If I am wicked, woe unto me; and if I am righteous, yet can I not lift up my head. I am full of disgrace; therefore see my affliction;
B018C010V016	18	10	16	For it increases. You hunt me as a fierce lion: and again you show yourself awesome against me.
B018C010V017	18	10	17	You renew your witnesses against me, and increase your indignation upon me; changes and war are ever with me.
B018C010V018	18	10	18	Why then have you brought me forth out of the womb? Oh that I had died, and no eye had seen me!
B018C010V019	18	10	19	I would have been as though I had not been; I would have been carried from the womb to the grave.
B018C010V020	18	10	20	Are not my days few? cease then, and let me alone, that I may take comfort a little,
B018C010V021	18	10	21	Before I go where I shall not return, even to the land of darkness and the shadow of death;
B018C010V022	18	10	22	A land of darkness, as darkness itself; and of the shadow of death, without any order, and where the light is as darkness.
B018C011V001	18	11	1	Then answered Zophar the Naamathite, and said,
B018C011V002	18	11	2	Should not the multitude of words be answered? and should a man full of talk be justified?
B018C011V003	18	11	3	Should your lies make men hold their peace? and when you mock, shall no man make you ashamed?
B018C011V004	18	11	4	For you have said, My doctrine is pure, and I am clean in your eyes.
B018C011V005	18	11	5	But oh that God would speak, and open his lips against you;
B018C011V006	18	11	6	And that he would show you the secrets of wisdom, that they are double to that which is! Know therefore that God exacts of you less than your iniquity deserves.
B018C011V007	18	11	7	Can you by searching find out God? can you find out the limits of the Almighty?
B018C011V008	18	11	8	It is as high as heaven; what can you do? deeper than Sheol; what can you know?
B018C011V009	18	11	9	The measure of it is longer than the earth, and broader than the sea.
B018C011V010	18	11	10	If he cuts off, and shuts up, or gathers together, then who can hinder him?
B018C011V011	18	11	11	For he knows vain men: he sees wickedness also; will he not then consider it?
B018C011V012	18	11	12	For a vain man will be wise, when a man is born a wild donkeyâ€™s colt.
B018C011V013	18	11	13	If you prepare your heart, and stretch out your hands toward him;
B018C011V014	18	11	14	If iniquity be in your hand, put it far away, and let not wickedness dwell in your tents.
B018C011V015	18	11	15	For then shall you lift up your face without spot; yea, you shall be steadfast, and shall not fear:
B018C011V016	18	11	16	Because you shall forget your misery, and remember it as waters that pass away:
B018C011V017	18	11	17	And your life shall be brighter than the noonday; you shall shine forth, you shall be as the morning.
B018C011V018	18	11	18	And you shall be secure, because there is hope; yea, you shall dig about you, and take your rest in safety.
B018C011V019	18	11	19	Also you shall lie down, and none shall make you afraid; yea, many shall entreat your favor.
B018C011V020	18	11	20	But the eyes of the wicked shall fail, and they shall not escape, and their hope shall be as one dying.
B018C012V001	18	12	1	And Job answered and said,
B018C012V002	18	12	2	No doubt you are the people, and wisdom shall die with you.
B018C012V003	18	12	3	But I have understanding as well as you; I am not inferior to you: yea, who knows not such things as these?
B018C012V004	18	12	4	I am as one mocked of his neighbor, who calls upon God, and he answers him: the just upright man is laughed to scorn.
B018C012V005	18	12	5	He that is ready to slip with his feet is like a lamp despised in the thought of him that is at ease.
B018C012V006	18	12	6	The tents of robbers prosper, and they that provoke God are secure; into whose hand God brings abundantly.
B018C012V007	18	12	7	But ask now the beasts, and they shall teach you; and the fowls of the air, and they shall tell you:
B018C012V008	18	12	8	Or speak to the earth, and it shall teach you: and the fish of the sea shall declare unto you.
B018C012V009	18	12	9	Who knows not among all these that the hand of the LORD has done this?
B018C012V010	18	12	10	In whose hand is the soul of every living thing, and the breath of all mankind.
B018C012V011	18	12	11	Does not the ear test words? and the mouth taste its food?
B018C012V012	18	12	12	With the ancient is wisdom; and in length of days understanding.
B018C012V013	18	12	13	With him is wisdom and strength, he has counsel and understanding.
B018C012V014	18	12	14	Behold, he breaks down, and it cannot be built again: he shuts up a man, and there can be no opening.
B018C012V015	18	12	15	Behold, he withholds the waters, and they dry up: also he sends them out, and they overturn the earth.
B018C012V016	18	12	16	With him is strength and wisdom: the deceived and the deceiver are his.
B018C012V017	18	12	17	He leads counselors away plundered, and makes the judges fools.
B018C012V018	18	12	18	He looses the bonds of kings, and girds their loins with a waistband.
B018C012V019	18	12	19	He leads princes away plundered, and overthrows the mighty.
B018C012V020	18	12	20	He takes away the speech of the trustworthy, and takes away the understanding of the aged.
B018C012V021	18	12	21	He pours contempt upon princes, and weakens the strength of the mighty.
B018C012V022	18	12	22	He uncovers deep things out of darkness, and brings out to light the shadow of death.
B018C012V023	18	12	23	He increases the nations, and destroys them: he enlarges the nations, and leads them away.
B018C012V024	18	12	24	He takes away the heart of the chiefs of the people of the earth, and causes them to wander in a wilderness where there is no way.
B018C012V025	18	12	25	They grope in the dark without light, and he makes them to stagger like a drunken man.
B018C013V001	18	13	1	Lo, my eye has seen all this, my ear has heard and understood it.
B018C013V002	18	13	2	What you know, the same do I know also: I am not inferior unto you.
B018C013V003	18	13	3	Surely I would speak to the Almighty, and I desire to reason with God.
B018C013V004	18	13	4	But you are forgers of lies, you are all physicians of no value.
B018C013V005	18	13	5	O that you would altogether hold your peace! and it should be your wisdom.
B018C013V006	18	13	6	Hear now my reasoning, and hearken to the pleadings of my lips.
B018C013V007	18	13	7	Will you speak wickedly for God? and talk deceitfully for him?
B018C013V008	18	13	8	Will you accept his person? will you contend for God?
B018C013V009	18	13	9	Is it good that he should search you out? or as one man mocks another, do you so mock him?
B018C013V010	18	13	10	He will surely reprove you, if you do secretly show partiality.
B018C013V011	18	13	11	Shall not his excellence make you afraid? and his dread fall upon you?
B018C013V012	18	13	12	Your proverbs are like unto ashes, your defenses are defenses of clay.
B018C013V013	18	13	13	Hold your peace, let me alone, that I may speak, and let come on me what will.
B018C013V014	18	13	14	Why do I take my flesh in my teeth, and put my life in my hand?
B018C013V015	18	13	15	Though he slay me, yet will I trust in him: but I will defend my own ways before him.
B018C013V016	18	13	16	He also shall be my salvation: for a hypocrite shall not come before him.
B018C013V017	18	13	17	Hear diligently my speech, and my declaration with your ears.
B018C013V018	18	13	18	Behold now, I have prepared my case; I know that I shall be justified.
B018C013V019	18	13	19	Who is he that will contend with me? for now, if I hold my tongue, I shall die.
B018C013V020	18	13	20	Only do not two things unto me: then will I not hide myself from you.
B018C013V021	18	13	21	Withdraw your hand far from me: and let not your dread make me afraid.
B018C013V022	18	13	22	Then call, and I will answer: or let me speak, and you answer me.
B018C013V023	18	13	23	How many are my iniquities and sins? make me know my transgression and my sin.
B018C013V024	18	13	24	Why hide you your face, and hold me for your enemy?
B018C013V025	18	13	25	Will you break a leaf driven to and fro? and will you pursue the dry stubble?
B018C013V026	18	13	26	For you write bitter things against me, and make me possess the iniquities of my youth.
B018C013V027	18	13	27	You put my feet also in the stocks, and watch closely all my paths; you set a bound to the soles of my feet.
B018C013V028	18	13	28	And he, like a rotten thing, consumes, as a garment that is moth-eaten.
B018C014V001	18	14	1	Man that is born of a woman is of few days, and full of trouble.
B018C014V002	18	14	2	He comes forth like a flower, and is cut down: he flees also as a shadow, and continues not.
B018C014V003	18	14	3	And do you open your eyes upon such a one, and bring me into judgment with you?
B018C014V004	18	14	4	Who can bring a clean thing out of an unclean? no one.
B018C014V005	18	14	5	Seeing his days are determined, the number of his months are with you, you have appointed his bounds that he cannot pass;
B018C014V006	18	14	6	Turn from him, that he may rest, till he shall accomplish, as a hireling, his day.
B018C014V007	18	14	7	For there is hope for a tree, if it is cut down, that it will sprout again, and that the tender shoots thereof will not cease.
B018C014V008	18	14	8	Though its root grows old in the earth, and its stump dies in the ground;
B018C014V009	18	14	9	Yet at the scent of water it will bud, and bring forth branches like a plant.
B018C014V010	18	14	10	But man dies, and wastes away: yea, man expires, and where is he?
B018C014V011	18	14	11	As the waters fail from the sea, and the river decays and dries up:
B018C014V012	18	14	12	So man lies down, and rises not: till the heavens be no more, they shall not awake, nor be raised out of their sleep.
B018C014V013	18	14	13	O that you would hide me in the grave, that you would conceal me, until your wrath is past, that you would appoint me a set time, and remember me!
B018C014V014	18	14	14	If a man dies, shall he live again? all the days of my appointed time will I wait, till my change comes.
B018C014V015	18	14	15	You shall call, and I will answer you: you will have a desire to the work of your hands.
B018C014V016	18	14	16	For now you number my steps: do not watch over my sin.
B018C014V017	18	14	17	My transgression is sealed up in a bag, and you sew up my iniquity.
B018C014V018	18	14	18	And surely the mountain falling, comes to nothing, and the rock is removed out of its place.
B018C014V019	18	14	19	The waters wear the stones: you wash away the things which grow out of the dust of the earth; and you destroy the hope of man.
B018C014V020	18	14	20	You prevail forever against him, and he passes: you change his countenance, and send him away.
B018C014V021	18	14	21	His sons come to honor, and he knows it not; and they are brought low, but he perceives it not of them.
B018C014V022	18	14	22	But his flesh upon him shall have pain, and his soul within him shall mourn.
B018C015V001	18	15	1	Then answered Eliphaz the Temanite, and said,
B018C015V002	18	15	2	Should a wise man utter vain knowledge, and fill his belly with the east wind?
B018C015V003	18	15	3	Should he reason with unprofitable talk? or with speeches with which he can do no good?
B018C015V004	18	15	4	Yea, you cast off fear, and restrain prayer before God.
B018C015V005	18	15	5	For your mouth utters your iniquity, and you choose the tongue of the crafty.
B018C015V006	18	15	6	Your own mouth condemns you, and not I: yea, your own lips testify against you.
B018C015V007	18	15	7	Are you the first man that was born? or were you made before the hills?
B018C015V008	18	15	8	Have you heard the council of God? and do you limit wisdom to yourself?
B018C015V009	18	15	9	What know you, that we know not? what understand you, which is not in us?
B018C015V010	18	15	10	With us are both the gray headed and very aged men, much older than your father.
B018C015V011	18	15	11	Are the consolations of God too small for you? on the word that deals gently with you?
B018C015V012	18	15	12	Why does your heart carry you away? and what do your eyes wink at,
B018C015V013	18	15	13	That you turn your spirit against God, and let such words go out of your mouth?
B018C015V014	18	15	14	What is man, that he should be clean? and he who is born of a woman, that he should be righteous?
B018C015V015	18	15	15	Behold, he puts no trust in his holy ones; yea, the heavens are not clean in his sight.
B018C015V016	18	15	16	How much more abominable and filthy is man, who drinks iniquity like water?
B018C015V017	18	15	17	I will show you, hear me; and that which I have seen I will declare;
B018C015V018	18	15	18	Which wise men have told from their fathers, and have not hid it:
B018C015V019	18	15	19	Unto whom alone the land was given, and no stranger passed among them.
B018C015V020	18	15	20	The wicked man travails with pain all his days, and the number of years is hidden for the oppressor.
B018C015V021	18	15	21	A dreadful sound is in his ears: in prosperity the destroyer shall come upon him.
B018C015V022	18	15	22	He believes not that he shall return out of darkness, and he is waited for by the sword.
B018C015V023	18	15	23	He wanders abroad for bread, saying, Where is it? he knows that the day of darkness is ready at his hand.
B018C015V024	18	15	24	Trouble and anguish shall make him afraid; they shall prevail against him, as a king ready for battle.
B018C015V025	18	15	25	For he stretches out his hand against God, and strengthens himself against the Almighty.
B018C015V026	18	15	26	He runs stubbornly against him, with his heavily embossed shield.
B018C015V027	18	15	27	Because he covers his face with his fatness, and makes heavy fat on his waist.
B018C015V028	18	15	28	And he dwells in desolate cities, and in houses which no man inhabits, which are ready to become heaps.
B018C015V029	18	15	29	He shall not be rich, neither shall his wealth continue, neither shall he overspread the earth with it.
B018C015V030	18	15	30	He shall not depart out of darkness; the flame shall dry up his branches, and by the breath of his mouth shall he go away.
B018C015V031	18	15	31	Let not him that is deceived trust in vanity: for futility shall be his reward.
B018C015V032	18	15	32	It shall be accomplished before his time, and his branch shall not be green.
B018C015V033	18	15	33	He shall shake off his unripe grapes like the vine, and shall cast off his blossom like the olive.
B018C015V034	18	15	34	For the congregation of hypocrites shall be desolate, and fire shall consume the tents of bribery.
B018C015V035	18	15	35	They conceive mischief, and bring forth vanity, and their heart prepares deceit.
B018C016V001	18	16	1	Then Job answered and said,
B018C016V002	18	16	2	I have heard many such things: miserable comforters are you all.
B018C016V003	18	16	3	Shall vain words have an end? or what emboldens you that you answer?
B018C016V004	18	16	4	I also could speak as you do: if your soul were in my soulâ€™s place, I could heap up words against you, and shake my head at you.
B018C016V005	18	16	5	But I would strengthen you with my mouth, and the moving of my lips would relieve your grief.
B018C016V006	18	16	6	Though I speak, my grief is not relieved: and though I forbear, how am I eased?
B018C016V007	18	16	7	But now he has made me weary: you have made desolate all my company.
B018C016V008	18	16	8	And you have filled me with wrinkles, which is a witness against me: and my leanness rising up in me bears witness to my face.
B018C016V009	18	16	9	He tears me in his wrath, who hates me: he gnashes upon me with his teeth; my enemy sharpens his eyes upon me.
B018C016V010	18	16	10	They have gaped upon me with their mouth; they have smitten me upon the cheek reproachfully; they have gathered themselves together against me.
B018C016V011	18	16	11	God has delivered me to the ungodly, and turned me over into the hands of the wicked.
B018C016V012	18	16	12	I was at ease, but he has broken me asunder: he has also taken me by my neck, and shaken me to pieces, and set me up for his mark.
B018C016V013	18	16	13	His archers surround me, he slashes my kidneys asunder, and does not spare; he pours out my gall upon the ground.
B018C016V014	18	16	14	He breaks me with breach upon breach, he runs upon me like a warrior.
B018C016V015	18	16	15	I have sewed sackcloth upon my skin, and laid my strength in the dust.
B018C016V016	18	16	16	My face is foul from weeping, and on my eyelids is the shadow of death;
B018C016V017	18	16	17	Not for any violence in my hands: also my prayer is pure.
B018C016V018	18	16	18	O earth, cover not my blood, and let my cry have no place.
B018C016V019	18	16	19	Also now, behold, my witness is in heaven, and my record is on high.
B018C016V020	18	16	20	My friends scorn me: but my eye pours out tears unto God.
B018C016V021	18	16	21	O that one might plead for a man with God, as a man pleads for his neighbor!
B018C016V022	18	16	22	When a few years have come, then I shall go the way where I shall not return.
B018C017V001	18	17	1	My breath is corrupt, my days are extinct, the grave is ready for me.
B018C017V002	18	17	2	Are there not mockers with me? and does not my eye continue in their provocation?
B018C017V003	18	17	3	Lay down a surety for me with you; who is he that will give surety for me?
B018C017V004	18	17	4	For you have hidden their heart from understanding: therefore shall you not exalt them.
B018C017V005	18	17	5	He that speaks flattery to his friends, even the eyes of his children shall fail.
B018C017V006	18	17	6	He has made me also a byword of the people; and I was as one before whom men spit.
B018C017V007	18	17	7	My eye also is dim by reason of sorrow, and all my members are like a shadow.
B018C017V008	18	17	8	Upright men shall be astonished at this, and the innocent shall stir up himself against the hypocrite.
B018C017V009	18	17	9	The righteous also shall hold to his way, and he that has clean hands shall be stronger and stronger.
B018C017V010	18	17	10	But as for you all, do you return, and come now: for I cannot find one wise man among you.
B018C017V011	18	17	11	My days are past, my purposes are broken off, even the thoughts of my heart.
B018C017V012	18	17	12	They change the night into day: the light is short because of darkness.
B018C017V013	18	17	13	If I wait, the grave is my house: I have made my bed in the darkness.
B018C017V014	18	17	14	I have said to corruption, You are my father: to the worm, You are my mother, and my sister.
B018C017V015	18	17	15	And where is now my hope? as for my hope, who shall see it?
B018C017V016	18	17	16	They shall go down to the gates of the pit, when our rest together is in the dust.
B018C018V001	18	18	1	Then answered Bildad the Shuhite, and said,
B018C018V002	18	18	2	How long will it be before you make an end of words? consider, and afterwards we will speak.
B018C018V003	18	18	3	Why are we counted as beasts, and regarded as vile in your sight?
B018C018V004	18	18	4	He tears himself in his anger: shall the earth be forsaken for you? and shall the rock be removed out of its place?
B018C018V005	18	18	5	Yea, the light of the wicked shall be put out, and the flame of his fire shall not shine.
B018C018V006	18	18	6	The light shall be dark in his tent, and his lamp shall be put out with him.
B018C018V007	18	18	7	The steps of his strength shall be shortened, and his own counsel shall cast him down.
B018C018V008	18	18	8	For he is cast into a net by his own feet, and he walks upon a snare.
B018C018V009	18	18	9	The trap shall take him by the heel, and a snare shall lay hold of him.
B018C018V010	18	18	10	The noose is laid for him on the ground, and a trap for him in the way.
B018C018V011	18	18	11	Terrors shall make him afraid on every side, and shall drive him to his feet.
B018C018V012	18	18	12	His strength shall be hunger-bitten, and destruction shall be ready at his side.
B018C018V013	18	18	13	It shall devour patches of his skin: even the firstborn of death shall devour his strength.
B018C018V014	18	18	14	His confidence shall be rooted out of his tent, and it shall bring him to the king of terrors.
B018C018V015	18	18	15	They shall dwell in his tent, who are none of his: brimstone shall be scattered upon his habitation.
B018C018V016	18	18	16	His roots shall be dried up beneath, and above shall his branch be cut off.
B018C018V017	18	18	17	His memory shall perish from the earth, and he shall have no name in the street.
B018C018V018	18	18	18	He shall be driven from light into darkness, and chased out of the world.
B018C018V019	18	18	19	He shall neither have son nor nephew among his people, nor any remaining in his dwellings.
B018C018V020	18	18	20	They that come after him shall be astounded at his day, as they that went before were frightened.
B018C018V021	18	18	21	Surely such are the dwellings of the wicked, and this is the place of him that knows not God.
B018C019V001	18	19	1	Then Job answered and said,
B018C019V002	18	19	2	How long will you torment my soul, and break me in pieces with words?
B018C019V003	18	19	3	These ten times have you reproached me: you are not ashamed that you have wronged me.
B018C019V004	18	19	4	And if indeed I have erred, my error remains with myself.
B018C019V005	18	19	5	If indeed you will magnify yourselves against me, and plead against me my reproach:
B018C019V006	18	19	6	Know now that God has overthrown me, and has compassed me with his net.
B018C019V007	18	19	7	Behold, I cry out concerning wrong, but I am not heard: I cry aloud, but there is no justice.
B018C019V008	18	19	8	He has fenced up my way that I cannot pass, and he has set darkness in my paths.
B018C019V009	18	19	9	He has stripped me of my glory, and taken the crown from my head.
B018C019V010	18	19	10	He has destroyed me on every side, and I am gone: and my hope has he removed like a tree.
B018C019V011	18	19	11	He has also kindled his wrath against me, and he counts me unto him as one of his enemies.
B018C019V012	18	19	12	His troops come together, and raise up their way against me, and encamp round about my tent.
B018C019V013	18	19	13	He has put my brethren far from me, and my acquaintances are wholly estranged from me.
B018C019V014	18	19	14	My kinsfolk have failed, and my close friends have forgotten me.
B018C019V015	18	19	15	They that dwell in my house, and my maidservants, count me as a stranger: I am an alien in their sight.
B018C019V016	18	19	16	I called my servant, and he gave me no answer; I entreated him with my mouth.
B018C019V017	18	19	17	My breath is repulsive to my wife, though I make supplication for the children of my own body.
B018C019V018	18	19	18	Yea, young children despised me; I arose, and they spoke against me.
B018C019V019	18	19	19	All my close friends abhorred me: and they whom I loved have turned against me.
B018C019V020	18	19	20	My bone clings to my skin and to my flesh, and I have escaped by the skin of my teeth.
B018C019V021	18	19	21	Have pity upon me, have pity upon me, O you my friends; for the hand of God has touched me.
B018C019V022	18	19	22	Why do you persecute me as God, and are not satisfied with my flesh?
B018C019V023	18	19	23	Oh that my words were now written! oh that they were printed in a book!
B018C019V024	18	19	24	That they were engraved with an iron pen and lead in the rock forever!
B018C019V025	18	19	25	For I know that my redeemer lives, and that he shall stand at the latter day upon the earth:
B018C019V026	18	19	26	And though after my skin is thus destroyed, yet in my flesh shall I see God:
B018C019V027	18	19	27	Whom I shall see for myself, and my eyes shall behold, and not another; though my heart be consumed within me.
B018C019V028	18	19	28	But you should say, Why persecute we him, seeing the root of the matter is found in me?
B018C019V029	18	19	29	Be yourselves afraid of the sword: for wrath brings the punishment of the sword, that you may know there is a judgment.
B018C020V001	18	20	1	Then answered Zophar the Naamathite, and said,
B018C020V002	18	20	2	Therefore do my thoughts cause me to answer, and for this I make haste.
B018C020V003	18	20	3	I have heard the rebuke of my reproach, and the spirit of my understanding causes me to answer.
B018C020V004	18	20	4	Know you not this of old, since man was placed upon the earth,
B018C020V005	18	20	5	That the triumphing of the wicked is short, and the joy of the hypocrite but for a moment?
B018C020V006	18	20	6	Though his haughtiness mounts up to the heavens, and his head reaches unto the clouds;
B018C020V007	18	20	7	Yet he shall perish forever like his own refuse: they who have seen him shall say, Where is he?
B018C020V008	18	20	8	He shall fly away as a dream, and shall not be found: yea, he shall be chased away as a vision of the night.
B018C020V009	18	20	9	The eye also which saw him shall see him no more; neither shall his place any more behold him.
B018C020V010	18	20	10	His children shall seek to please the poor, and his hands shall restore their goods.
B018C020V011	18	20	11	His bones are full of the sin of his youth, which shall lie down with him in the dust.
B018C020V012	18	20	12	Though wickedness be sweet in his mouth, though he hide it under his tongue;
B018C020V013	18	20	13	Though he spare it, and forsake it not; but keep it still within his mouth:
B018C020V014	18	20	14	Yet his food in his body is soured, it is the gall of asps within him.
B018C020V015	18	20	15	He has swallowed down riches, and he shall vomit them up again: God shall cast them out of his belly.
B018C020V016	18	20	16	He shall suck the poison of asps: the viperâ€™s tongue shall slay him.
B018C020V017	18	20	17	He shall not see the rivers, the brooks flowing with honey and butter.
B018C020V018	18	20	18	That which he labored for shall he restore, and shall not swallow it down: from the proceeds of business he shall not rejoice.
B018C020V019	18	20	19	Because he has oppressed and has forsaken the poor; because he has violently taken away a house which he built not;
B018C020V020	18	20	20	Surely he shall not feel quietness in his heart, he shall not save of that which he desired.
B018C020V021	18	20	21	There shall none of his food be left; therefore shall no man look for his goods.
B018C020V022	18	20	22	In the fullness of his sufficiency he shall be in distress: every hand of the wicked shall come upon him.
B018C020V023	18	20	23	When he is about to fill his belly, God shall cast the fury of his wrath upon him, and shall rain it upon him while he is eating.
B018C020V024	18	20	24	He shall flee from the iron weapon, and the bow of bronze shall strike him through.
B018C020V025	18	20	25	It is drawn, and comes out of the body; yea, the glittering sword comes out of his gall: terrors are upon him.
B018C020V026	18	20	26	All darkness shall be laid up for his treasures: a fire not blown upon shall consume him; it shall go ill with him who is left in his tent.
B018C020V027	18	20	27	The heaven shall reveal his iniquity; and the earth shall rise up against him.
B018C020V028	18	20	28	The increase of his house shall depart, and his goods shall flow away in the day of his wrath.
B018C020V029	18	20	29	This is the portion of a wicked man from God, and the heritage appointed unto him by God.
B018C021V001	18	21	1	But Job answered and said,
B018C021V002	18	21	2	Hear diligently my speech, and let this be your consolation.
B018C021V003	18	21	3	Bear with me that I may speak; and after that I have spoken, mock on.
B018C021V004	18	21	4	As for me, is my complaint to man? and if it were so, why should not my spirit be troubled?
B018C021V005	18	21	5	Look at me, and be astonished, and lay your hand upon your mouth.
B018C021V006	18	21	6	Even when I remember I am afraid, and trembling takes hold on my flesh.
B018C021V007	18	21	7	Why do the wicked live, become old, yea, are mighty in power?
B018C021V008	18	21	8	Their descendants are established in their sight with them, and their offspring before their eyes.
B018C021V009	18	21	9	Their houses are safe from fear, neither is the rod of God upon them.
B018C021V010	18	21	10	Their bull breeds, and fails not; their cow calves, and casts not her calf.
B018C021V011	18	21	11	They send forth their little ones like a flock, and their children dance.
B018C021V012	18	21	12	They sing to the tambourine and harp, and rejoice at the sound of the flute.
B018C021V013	18	21	13	They spend their days in wealth, and in a moment go down to the grave.
B018C021V014	18	21	14	Therefore they say unto God, Depart from us; for we desire not the knowledge of your ways.
B018C021V015	18	21	15	What is the Almighty, that we should serve him? and what profit should we have, if we pray unto him?
B018C021V016	18	21	16	Lo, their prosperity is not in their hand: the counsel of the wicked is far from me.
B018C021V017	18	21	17	How often is the lamp of the wicked put out! and how often comes their destruction upon them! God distributes sorrows in his anger.
B018C021V018	18	21	18	They are as stubble before the wind, and as chaff that the storm carries away.
B018C021V019	18	21	19	God lays up his iniquity for his children: he recompenses him, and he shall know it.
B018C021V020	18	21	20	His eyes shall see his destruction, and he shall drink of the wrath of the Almighty.
B018C021V021	18	21	21	For what pleasure has he in his house after him, when the number of his months is cut off in the midst?
B018C021V022	18	21	22	Shall any teach God knowledge? seeing he judges those that are on high.
B018C021V023	18	21	23	One dies in his full strength, being wholly at ease and quiet.
B018C021V024	18	21	24	His breasts are full of milk, and his bones are moistened with marrow.
B018C021V025	18	21	25	And another dies in the bitterness of his soul, and never eats with pleasure.
B018C021V026	18	21	26	They shall lie down alike in the dust, and the worms shall cover them.
B018C021V027	18	21	27	Behold, I know your thoughts, and the devices which you wrongfully imagine against me.
B018C021V028	18	21	28	For you say, Where is the house of the prince? and where are the dwelling places of the wicked?
B018C021V029	18	21	29	Have you not asked them that go by the way? and do you not know their evidences,
B018C021V030	18	21	30	That the wicked are reserved to the day of destruction? they shall be brought forth to the day of wrath.
B018C021V031	18	21	31	Who shall declare his way to his face? and who shall repay him what he has done?
B018C021V032	18	21	32	Yet shall he be brought to the grave, and shall remain in the tomb.
B018C021V033	18	21	33	The clods of the valley shall be sweet unto him, and every man shall follow after him, as there are innumerable gone before him.
B018C021V034	18	21	34	How then do you comfort me in vain, seeing in your answers there remains falsehood?
B018C022V001	18	22	1	Then Eliphaz the Temanite answered and said,
B018C022V002	18	22	2	Can a man be profitable unto God, as he that is wise may be profitable unto himself?
B018C022V003	18	22	3	Is it any pleasure to the Almighty, that you are righteous? or is it gain to him, that you make your ways blameless?
B018C022V004	18	22	4	Will he reprove you for fear of you? will he enter with you into judgment?
B018C022V005	18	22	5	Is not your wickedness great? and your iniquities without end?
B018C022V006	18	22	6	For you have taken a pledge from your brother for nothing, and stripped the naked of their clothing.
B018C022V007	18	22	7	You have not given water to the weary to drink, and you have withheld bread from the hungry.
B018C022V008	18	22	8	But as for the mighty man, he had the earth; and the honorable man dwelt in it.
B018C022V009	18	22	9	You have sent widows away empty, and the arms of the fatherless have been broken.
B018C022V010	18	22	10	Therefore snares are round about you, and sudden fear troubles you;
B018C022V011	18	22	11	Or darkness, that you can not see; and abundance of waters cover you.
B018C022V012	18	22	12	Is not God in the height of heaven? and behold the height of the stars, how high they are!
B018C022V013	18	22	13	And you say, How does God know? can he judge through the dark cloud?
B018C022V014	18	22	14	Thick clouds are a covering to him, that he sees not; and he walks in the circle of heaven.
B018C022V015	18	22	15	Have you marked the old way which wicked men have trodden?
B018C022V016	18	22	16	Who were cut down before their time, whose foundation was swept away with a flood:
B018C022V017	18	22	17	Who said unto God, Depart from us: and what can the Almighty do to us?
B018C022V018	18	22	18	Yet he filled their houses with good things: but the counsel of the wicked is far from me.
B018C022V019	18	22	19	The righteous see it, and are glad: and the innocent laugh them to scorn.
B018C022V020	18	22	20	Surely our substance is not cut down, but the remnant of them the fire consumes.
B018C022V021	18	22	21	Acquaint now yourself with him, and be at peace: thereby good shall come unto you.
B018C022V022	18	22	22	Receive, I pray you, the law from his mouth, and lay up his words in your heart.
B018C022V023	18	22	23	If you return to the Almighty, you shall be built up, you shall put away iniquity far from your tents.
B018C022V024	18	22	24	Then shall you lay up gold as dust, and the gold of Ophir as the stones of the brooks.
B018C022V025	18	22	25	Yea, the Almighty shall be your defense, and you shall have plenty of silver.
B018C022V026	18	22	26	For then shall you have your delight in the Almighty, and shall lift up your face unto God.
B018C022V027	18	22	27	You shall make your prayer unto him, and he shall hear you, and you shall pay your vows.
B018C022V028	18	22	28	You shall also decree a thing, and it shall be established for you: and the light shall shine upon your ways.
B018C022V029	18	22	29	When men are cast down, then you shall say, There is lifting up; and he shall save the humble person.
B018C022V030	18	22	30	He shall deliver the innocent man: and he is delivered by the pureness of your hands.
B018C023V001	18	23	1	Then Job answered and said,
B018C023V002	18	23	2	Even today is my complaint bitter: my hand is heavy in spite of my groaning.
B018C023V003	18	23	3	Oh that I knew where I might find him! that I might come even to his seat!
B018C023V004	18	23	4	I would order my cause before him, and fill my mouth with arguments.
B018C023V005	18	23	5	I would know the words which he would answer me, and understand what he would say unto me.
B018C023V006	18	23	6	Will he plead against me with his great power? No; but he would put strength in me.
B018C023V007	18	23	7	There the righteous might reason with him; so should I be delivered forever from my judge.
B018C023V008	18	23	8	Behold, I go forward, but he is not there; and backward, but I cannot perceive him:
B018C023V009	18	23	9	On the left hand, where he does work, but I cannot behold him: he hides himself on the right hand, that I cannot see him:
B018C023V010	18	23	10	But he knows the way that I take: when he has tested me, I shall come forth as gold.
B018C023V011	18	23	11	My foot has held fast to his steps, his way have I kept, and not turned aside.
B018C023V012	18	23	12	Neither have I gone back from the commandment of his lips; I have esteemed the words of his mouth more than my necessary food.
B018C023V013	18	23	13	But he is of one mind, and who can turn him? and what his soul desires, even that he does.
B018C023V014	18	23	14	For he performs the thing that is appointed for me: and many such things are with him.
B018C023V015	18	23	15	Therefore am I troubled at his presence: when I consider, I am afraid of him.
B018C023V016	18	23	16	For God makes my heart soft, and the Almighty troubles me:
B018C023V017	18	23	17	Because I was not cut off before the darkness, neither has he covered the darkness from my face.
B018C024V001	18	24	1	Why, seeing times are not hidden from the Almighty, do they that know him not see his days?
B018C024V002	18	24	2	Some remove the landmarks; they violently take away flocks, and feed on them.
B018C024V003	18	24	3	They drive away the donkey of the fatherless, they take the widowâ€™s ox for a pledge.
B018C024V004	18	24	4	They drive the needy off the road: the poor of the earth hide themselves together.
B018C024V005	18	24	5	Behold, as wild donkeys in the desert, go they forth to their work; rising early for a prey: the wilderness yields food for them and for their children.
B018C024V006	18	24	6	They reap every one his grain in the field: and they gather the vineyard of the wicked.
B018C024V007	18	24	7	They cause the naked to lodge without clothing, that they have no covering in the cold.
B018C024V008	18	24	8	They are wet with the showers of the mountains, and embrace the rock for want of a shelter.
B018C024V009	18	24	9	They pluck the fatherless from the breast, and take a pledge from the poor.
B018C024V010	18	24	10	They cause him to go naked without clothing, and they take away the sheaves from the hungry;
B018C024V011	18	24	11	Who make oil within their walls, and tread their winepresses, yet suffer thirst.
B018C024V012	18	24	12	Men groan from out of the city, and the soul of the wounded cries out: yet God charges not folly to them.
B018C024V013	18	24	13	They are of those that rebel against the light; they know not its ways, nor abide in its paths.
B018C024V014	18	24	14	The murderer rising with the light kills the poor and needy, and in the night is as a thief.
B018C024V015	18	24	15	The eye also of the adulterer waits for the twilight, saying, No eye shall see me: and disguises his face.
B018C024V016	18	24	16	In the dark they dig through houses, which they had marked for themselves in the daytime: they know not the light.
B018C024V017	18	24	17	For the morning is to them even as the shadow of death: if one recognizes them, they are in the terrors of the shadow of death.
B018C024V018	18	24	18	They are swift as the waters; their portion is cursed in the earth: no one turns into the way of the vineyards.
B018C024V019	18	24	19	Drought and heat consume the snow waters: so does the grave those who have sinned.
B018C024V020	18	24	20	The womb shall forget him; the worm shall feed sweetly on him; he shall be no more remembered; and wickedness shall be broken as a tree.
B018C024V021	18	24	21	He evil treats the barren that bears not: and does not good to the widow.
B018C024V022	18	24	22	He draws also the mighty with his power: he rises up, but no man is sure of life.
B018C024V023	18	24	23	Though it be given him to be in safety, he rests; yet his eyes are upon their ways.
B018C024V024	18	24	24	They are exalted for a little while, but are gone and brought low; they are taken out of the way as all others, and cut off as the tops of the ears of grain.
B018C024V025	18	24	25	And if it be not so now, who will make me a liar, and make my speech worth nothing?
B018C025V001	18	25	1	Then answered Bildad the Shuhite, and said,
B018C025V002	18	25	2	Dominion and fear are with him, he makes peace in his high places.
B018C025V003	18	25	3	Is there any number to his armies? and upon whom does not his light arise?
B018C025V004	18	25	4	How then can man be justified with God? or how can he be clean that is born of a woman?
B018C025V005	18	25	5	Behold even to the moon, and it shines not; yea, the stars are not pure in his sight.
B018C025V006	18	25	6	How much less man, that is a worm? and the son of man, who is a worm?
B018C026V001	18	26	1	But Job answered and said,
B018C026V002	18	26	2	How have you helped him that is without power? how save you the arm that has no strength?
B018C026V003	18	26	3	How have you counseled him that has no wisdom? and how have you plentifully declared the thing as it is?
B018C026V004	18	26	4	To whom have you uttered words? and whose spirit came from you?
B018C026V005	18	26	5	Dead things are formed from under the waters, and the inhabitants thereof.
B018C026V006	18	26	6	Sheol is naked before him, and destruction has no covering.
B018C026V007	18	26	7	He stretches out the north over the empty place, and hangs the earth upon nothing.
B018C026V008	18	26	8	He binds up the waters in his thick clouds; and the cloud is not torn under them.
B018C026V009	18	26	9	He holds back the face of his throne, and spreads his cloud upon it.
B018C026V010	18	26	10	He has drawn a circle on the waters at the boundary where the day and night come together.
B018C026V011	18	26	11	The pillars of heaven tremble and are astonished at his rebuke.
B018C026V012	18	26	12	He divides the sea with his power, and by his understanding he strikes through the storm.
B018C026V013	18	26	13	By his spirit he has adorned the heavens; his hand has pierced the fleeing serpent.
B018C026V014	18	26	14	Lo, these are only parts of his ways: and how little a whisper is heard of him? but the thunder of his power who can understand?
B018C027V001	18	27	1	Moreover Job continued his discourse, and said,
B018C027V002	18	27	2	As God lives, who has taken away my right; and the Almighty, who has made bitter my soul;
B018C027V003	18	27	3	All the while my breath is in me, and the spirit of God is in my nostrils;
B018C027V004	18	27	4	My lips shall not speak wickedness, nor my tongue utter deceit.
B018C027V005	18	27	5	God forbid that I should justify you: till I die I will not remove my integrity from me.
B018C027V006	18	27	6	My righteousness I hold fast, and will not let it go: my heart shall not reproach me so long as I live.
B018C027V007	18	27	7	Let my enemy be as the wicked, and he that rises up against me as the unrighteous.
B018C027V008	18	27	8	For what is the hope of the hypocrite, though he has gained, when God takes away his soul?
B018C027V009	18	27	9	Will God hear his cry when trouble comes upon him?
B018C027V010	18	27	10	Will he delight himself in the Almighty? will he always call upon God?
B018C027V011	18	27	11	I will teach you by the hand of God: that which is with the Almighty will I not conceal.
B018C027V012	18	27	12	Behold, all you yourselves have seen it; why then are you thus altogether vain?
B018C027V013	18	27	13	This is the portion of a wicked man with God, and the heritage of oppressors, which they shall receive of the Almighty.
B018C027V014	18	27	14	If his children are multiplied, it is for the sword: and his offspring shall not be satisfied with bread.
B018C027V015	18	27	15	Those that remain of him shall be buried in death: and his widows shall not weep.
B018C027V016	18	27	16	Though he heap up silver as the dust, and pile up clothing as the clay;
B018C027V017	18	27	17	He may prepare it, but the just shall put it on, and the innocent shall divide the silver.
B018C027V018	18	27	18	He builds his house like a moth, and like a booth that the keeper makes.
B018C027V019	18	27	19	The rich man shall lie down, but he shall not be gathered: he opens his eyes, and he is not.
B018C027V020	18	27	20	Terrors take hold on him as waters, a tempest steals him away in the night.
B018C027V021	18	27	21	The east wind carries him away, and he is gone: and as a storm hurls him out of his place.
B018C027V022	18	27	22	For God shall cast upon him, and not spare: he would scarcely flee out of his hand.
B018C027V023	18	27	23	Men shall clap their hands at him, and shall hiss him out of his place.
B018C028V001	18	28	1	Surely there is a vein for the silver, and a place for gold where they refine it.
B018C028V002	18	28	2	Iron is taken out of the earth, and copper is smelted out of the ore.
B018C028V003	18	28	3	Man sets an end to darkness, and searches out all recesses for ore in darkness, and the shadow of death.
B018C028V004	18	28	4	He breaks open a shaft away from the inhabitants; even in places forgotten of the foot: they are gone away from men, they swing to and fro.
B018C028V005	18	28	5	As for the earth, out of it comes bread: but under it is turned up as it were fire.
B018C028V006	18	28	6	The stones of it are the place of sapphires: and it has dust of gold.
B018C028V007	18	28	7	There is a path which no fowl knows, and which the falconâ€™s eye has not seen:
B018C028V008	18	28	8	The lionâ€™s whelps have not trodden it, nor the fierce lion passed by it.
B018C028V009	18	28	9	He puts forth his hand upon the flinty rock; he overturns the mountains by the roots.
B018C028V010	18	28	10	He cuts out rivers in the rocks; and his eye sees every precious thing.
B018C028V011	18	28	11	He binds the streams from overflowing; and the thing that is hid brings he forth to light.
B018C028V012	18	28	12	But where shall wisdom be found? and where is the place of understanding?
B018C028V013	18	28	13	Man knows not the price thereof; neither is it found in the land of the living.
B018C028V014	18	28	14	The deep says, It is not in me: and the sea says, It is not with me.
B018C028V015	18	28	15	It cannot be gotten for gold, neither shall silver be weighed for the price thereof.
B018C028V016	18	28	16	It cannot be valued with the gold of Ophir, with the precious onyx, or the sapphire.
B018C028V017	18	28	17	The gold and the crystal cannot equal it: and the exchange of it shall not be for jewels of fine gold.
B018C028V018	18	28	18	No mention shall be made of coral, or of crystal: for the price of wisdom is above rubies.
B018C028V019	18	28	19	The topaz of Ethiopia shall not equal it, neither shall it be valued with pure gold.
B018C028V020	18	28	20	From where then comes wisdom? and where is the place of understanding?
B018C028V021	18	28	21	Seeing it is hid from the eyes of all living, and concealed from the fowls of the air.
B018C028V022	18	28	22	Destruction and death say, We have heard the fame of it with our ears.
B018C028V023	18	28	23	God understands its way, and he knows its place.
B018C028V024	18	28	24	For he looks to the ends of the earth, and sees under the whole heaven;
B018C028V025	18	28	25	To make the weight for the wind; and he apportions the waters by measure.
B018C028V026	18	28	26	When he made a decree for the rain, and a way for the lightning of the thunder:
B018C028V027	18	28	27	Then did he see it, and declare it; he prepared it, yea, and searched it out.
B018C028V028	18	28	28	And unto man he said, Behold, the fear of the Lord, that is wisdom; and to depart from evil is understanding.
B018C029V001	18	29	1	Moreover Job continued his discourse, and said,
B018C029V002	18	29	2	Oh that I were as in months past, as in the days when God preserved me;
B018C029V003	18	29	3	When his lamp shined upon my head, and when by his light I walked through darkness;
B018C029V004	18	29	4	As I was in the days of my youth, when the secret of God was upon my tent;
B018C029V005	18	29	5	When the Almighty was yet with me, when my children were about me;
B018C029V006	18	29	6	When I washed my steps with butter, and the rock poured me out rivers of oil;
B018C029V007	18	29	7	When I went out to the gate of the city, when I prepared my seat in the open square!
B018C029V008	18	29	8	The young men saw me, and hid themselves: and the aged arose, and stood up.
B018C029V009	18	29	9	The princes refrained from talking, and laid their hand on their mouth.
B018C029V010	18	29	10	The nobles held their peace, and their tongue cleaved to the roof of their mouth.
B018C029V011	18	29	11	When the ear heard me, then it blessed me; and when the eye saw me, it gave witness to me:
B018C029V012	18	29	12	Because I delivered the poor that cried, and the fatherless, and him that had none to help him.
B018C029V013	18	29	13	The blessing of him that was ready to perish came upon me: and I caused the widowâ€™s heart to sing for joy.
B018C029V014	18	29	14	I put on righteousness, and it clothed me: my justice was as a robe and a turban.
B018C029V015	18	29	15	I was eyes to the blind, and feet was I to the lame.
B018C029V016	18	29	16	I was a father to the poor: and the cause which I knew not I searched out.
B018C029V017	18	29	17	And I broke the fangs of the wicked, and plucked the spoil out of his teeth.
B018C029V018	18	29	18	Then I said, I shall die in my nest, and I shall multiply my days as the sand.
B018C029V019	18	29	19	My root was spread out to the waters, and the dew lay all night upon my branch.
B018C029V020	18	29	20	My glory was fresh in me, and my bow was renewed in my hand.
B018C029V021	18	29	21	Unto me men gave ear, and waited, and kept silence at my counsel.
B018C029V022	18	29	22	After my words they spoke not again; and my speech dropped upon them.
B018C029V023	18	29	23	And they waited for me as for the rain; and they opened their mouth wide as for the latter rain.
B018C029V024	18	29	24	If I mocked them, they believed it not; and the light of my countenance they cast not down.
B018C029V025	18	29	25	I chose out their way, and sat as chief, and dwelt like a king in the army, as one that comforts the mourners.
B018C030V001	18	30	1	But now they that are younger than I hold me in derision, whose fathers I would have disdained to have set with the dogs of my flock.
B018C030V002	18	30	2	Yea, how might the strength of their hands profit me, in whom vigor has perished?
B018C030V003	18	30	3	From want and famine they are gaunt; fleeing of late into the wilderness, desolate and waste.
B018C030V004	18	30	4	Who pick mallows by the bushes, and juniper roots for their food.
B018C030V005	18	30	5	They were driven forth from among men, (they cried after them as after a thief;)
B018C030V006	18	30	6	To dwell in the clefts of the valleys, in caves of the earth, and in the rocks.
B018C030V007	18	30	7	Among the bushes they brayed; under the nettles they were gathered together.
B018C030V008	18	30	8	They were children of fools, yea, children of base men: they were viler than the earth.
B018C030V009	18	30	9	And now am I their song, yea, I am their byword.
B018C030V010	18	30	10	They abhor me, they flee far from me, and hesitate not to spit in my face.
B018C030V011	18	30	11	Because he has loosed my cord, and afflicted me, they have also cast off restraint before me.
B018C030V012	18	30	12	Upon my right hand rise the youth; they push away my feet, and they raise up against me the ways of their destruction.
B018C030V013	18	30	13	They mar my path, they set forward my calamity, they have no helper.
B018C030V014	18	30	14	They came upon me as a wide breaking in of waters: in the desolation they rolled themselves upon me.
B018C030V015	18	30	15	Terrors are turned upon me: they pursue my honor as the wind: and my welfare passes away as a cloud.
B018C030V016	18	30	16	And now my soul is poured out upon me; the days of affliction have taken hold upon me.
B018C030V017	18	30	17	My bones are pierced in me in the night season: and my sinews take no rest.
B018C030V018	18	30	18	By the great force of my disease is my garment changed: it binds me about as the collar of my coat.
B018C030V019	18	30	19	He has cast me into the mire, and I am become like dust and ashes.
B018C030V020	18	30	20	I cry unto you, and you do not hear me: I stand up, and you regard me not.
B018C030V021	18	30	21	You have become cruel to me: with your strong hand you oppose yourself against me.
B018C030V022	18	30	22	You lift me up to the wind; you cause me to ride upon it, and spoil my substance.
B018C030V023	18	30	23	For I know that you will bring me to death, and to the house appointed for all living.
B018C030V024	18	30	24	Yet he will not stretch out his hand to the grave, though they cry out in his destruction.
B018C030V025	18	30	25	Did I not weep for him that was in trouble? was not my soul grieved for the poor?
B018C030V026	18	30	26	When I looked for good, then evil came unto me: and when I waited for light, there came darkness.
B018C030V027	18	30	27	My heart is in turmoil, and rests not: the days of affliction confront me.
B018C030V028	18	30	28	I went mourning but not in the sun: I stood up, and I cried in the congregation.
B018C030V029	18	30	29	I am a brother to jackals, and a companion to ostriches.
B018C030V030	18	30	30	My skin is black upon me, and my bones are burned with heat.
B018C030V031	18	30	31	My harp also is turned to mourning, and my flute into the voice of them that weep.
B018C031V001	18	31	1	I made a covenant with my eyes; why then should I think upon a maiden?
B018C031V002	18	31	2	For what portion of God is there from above? and what inheritance of the Almighty from on high?
B018C031V003	18	31	3	Is not destruction to the wicked? and a disaster to the workers of iniquity?
B018C031V004	18	31	4	Does not he see my ways, and count all my steps?
B018C031V005	18	31	5	If I have walked with vanity, or if my foot has hastened to deceit;
B018C031V006	18	31	6	Let me be weighed in an even balance, that God may know my integrity.
B018C031V007	18	31	7	If my step has turned out of the way, and my heart walked after my eyes, and if any spot has cleaved to my hands;
B018C031V008	18	31	8	Then let me sow, and let another eat; yea, let my offspring be rooted out.
B018C031V009	18	31	9	If my heart has been deceived by a woman, or if I have laid wait at my neighborâ€™s door;
B018C031V010	18	31	10	Then let my wife grind for another, and let others bow down upon her.
B018C031V011	18	31	11	For this is a heinous crime; yea, it is an iniquity to be punished by the judges.
B018C031V012	18	31	12	For it is a fire that consumes to destruction, and would root out all my increase.
B018C031V013	18	31	13	If I did despise the cause of my manservant or of my maidservant, when they contended with me;
B018C031V014	18	31	14	What then shall I do when God rises up? and when he comes, what shall I answer him?
B018C031V015	18	31	15	Did not he that made me in the womb make him? and did not one fashion us in the womb?
B018C031V016	18	31	16	If I have withheld the poor from their desire, or have caused the eyes of the widow to fail;
B018C031V017	18	31	17	Or have eaten my morsel alone, and the fatherless has not eaten of it;
B018C031V018	18	31	18	(For from my youth he was brought up with me, as with a father, and I have guided him from my motherâ€™s womb;)
B018C031V019	18	31	19	If I have seen any perish for want of clothing, or any poor without covering;
B018C031V020	18	31	20	If his heart has not blessed me, and if he was not warmed with the fleece of my sheep;
B018C031V021	18	31	21	If I have lifted up my hand against the fatherless, when I saw I had help in the gate:
B018C031V022	18	31	22	Then let my arm fall from my shoulder blade, and my arm be broken from its socket.
B018C031V023	18	31	23	For destruction from God was a terror to me, and by reason of his majesty I could not endure.
B018C031V024	18	31	24	If I have made gold my hope, or have said to the fine gold, You are my confidence;
B018C031V025	18	31	25	If I rejoiced because my wealth was great, and because my hand had gotten much;
B018C031V026	18	31	26	If I beheld the sun when it shined, or the moon moving in brightness;
B018C031V027	18	31	27	And my heart has been secretly enticed, or my mouth has kissed my hand:
B018C031V028	18	31	28	This also would be an iniquity to be punished by the judge: for I should have denied the God that is above.
B018C031V029	18	31	29	If I rejoiced at the destruction of him that hated me, or lifted up myself when evil found him:
B018C031V030	18	31	30	Neither have I suffered my mouth to sin by wishing a curse to his soul.
B018C031V031	18	31	31	If the men of my tent have not, Oh that we had of his meat! we cannot be satisfied.
B018C031V032	18	31	32	The stranger did not lodge in the street: but I opened my doors to the traveler.
B018C031V033	18	31	33	If I covered my transgressions as Adam, by hiding my iniquity in my bosom:
B018C031V034	18	31	34	Did I fear a great multitude, or did the contempt of families terrify me, that I kept silence, and went not out of the door?
B018C031V035	18	31	35	Oh that one would hear me! behold, my desire is, that the Almighty would answer me, and that my adversary had written a book.
B018C031V036	18	31	36	Surely I would take it upon my shoulder, and bind it as a crown to me.
B018C031V037	18	31	37	I would declare unto him the number of my steps; as a prince would I go near unto him.
B018C031V038	18	31	38	If my land cries against me, and its furrows likewise complain;
B018C031V039	18	31	39	If I have eaten its fruit without payment, or have caused its owners to lose their life:
B018C031V040	18	31	40	Let thistles grow instead of wheat, and weeds instead of barley. The words of Job are ended.
B018C032V001	18	32	1	So these three men ceased to answer Job, because he was righteous in his own eyes.
B018C032V002	18	32	2	Then was kindled the wrath of Elihu the son of Barachel the Buzite, of the family of Ram: against Job was his wrath aroused, because he justified himself rather than God.
B018C032V003	18	32	3	Also against his three friends was his wrath aroused, because they had found no answer, and yet had condemned Job.
B018C032V004	18	32	4	Now Elihu had waited till Job had spoken, because they were older than he.
B018C032V005	18	32	5	When Elihu saw that there was no answer in the mouth of these three men, then his wrath was aroused.
B018C032V006	18	32	6	And Elihu the son of Barachel the Buzite answered and said, I am young, and you are very old; therefore I was afraid, and dared not show you my opinion.
B018C032V007	18	32	7	I said, Days should speak, and multitude of years should teach wisdom.
B018C032V008	18	32	8	But there is a spirit in man: and the inspiration of the Almighty gives him understanding.
B018C032V009	18	32	9	Great men are not always wise: neither do the aged understand justice.
B018C032V010	18	32	10	Therefore I say, Hearken to me; I also will show my opinion.
B018C032V011	18	32	11	Behold, I waited for your words; I gave ear to your reasons, while you searched out what to say.
B018C032V012	18	32	12	Yea, I attended unto you, and, behold, there was none of you that convinced Job, or that answered his words:
B018C032V013	18	32	13	Lest you should say, We have found out wisdom: God vanquishes him, not man.
B018C032V014	18	32	14	Now he has not directed his words against me: neither will I answer him with your speeches.
B018C032V015	18	32	15	They were amazed, they answered no more: they left off speaking.
B018C032V016	18	32	16	When I had waited, (for they spoke not, but stood still, and answered no more;)
B018C032V017	18	32	17	I said, I will answer also my part, I also will show my opinion.
B018C032V018	18	32	18	For I am full of words, the spirit within me constrains me.
B018C032V019	18	32	19	Behold, my belly is as wine which has no vent; it is ready to burst like new wineskins.
B018C032V020	18	32	20	I will speak, that I may be refreshed: I will open my lips and answer.
B018C032V021	18	32	21	Let me not, I pray you, accept any manâ€™s person, neither let me give flattery unto man.
B018C032V022	18	32	22	For I know not how to give flattery; in so doing my maker would soon take me away.
B018C033V001	18	33	1	Therefore, Job, I pray you, hear my speeches, and hearken to all my words.
B018C033V002	18	33	2	Behold, now I have opened my mouth, my tongue has spoken in my mouth.
B018C033V003	18	33	3	My words shall be of the uprightness of my heart: and my lips shall utter knowledge clearly.
B018C033V004	18	33	4	The spirit of God has made me, and the breath of the Almighty has given me life.
B018C033V005	18	33	5	If you can answer me, set your words in order before me, stand up.
B018C033V006	18	33	6	Behold, I am according to your wish in Godâ€™s stead: I also am formed out of the clay.
B018C033V007	18	33	7	Behold, my terror shall not make you afraid, neither shall my hand be heavy upon you.
B018C033V008	18	33	8	Surely you have spoken in my hearing, and I have heard the voice of your words, saying,
B018C033V009	18	33	9	I am clean without transgression, I am innocent; neither is there iniquity in me.
B018C033V010	18	33	10	Behold, he finds occasions against me, he counts me for his enemy,
B018C033V011	18	33	11	He puts my feet in the stocks, he marks all my paths.
B018C033V012	18	33	12	Behold, in this you are not just: I will answer you, for God is greater than man.
B018C033V013	18	33	13	Why do you strive against him? for he gives not account of any of his matters.
B018C033V014	18	33	14	For God speaks once, yea twice, yet man perceives it not.
B018C033V015	18	33	15	In a dream, in a vision of the night, when deep sleep falls upon men, in slumberings upon the bed;
B018C033V016	18	33	16	Then he opens the ears of men, and seals their instruction,
B018C033V017	18	33	17	That he may turn man from his purpose, and hide pride from man.
B018C033V018	18	33	18	He keeps back his soul from the pit, and his life from perishing by the sword.
B018C033V019	18	33	19	He is chastened also with pain upon his bed, and the multitude of his bones with strong pain:
B018C033V020	18	33	20	So that his life abhors bread, and his soul the choicest food.
B018C033V021	18	33	21	His flesh is consumed away, that it cannot be seen; and his bones that were not seen now stick out.
B018C033V022	18	33	22	Yea, his soul draws near unto the grave, and his life to those who bring death.
B018C033V023	18	33	23	If there be a messenger with him, a mediator, one of a thousand, to show unto man his uprightness:
B018C033V024	18	33	24	Then he is gracious unto him, and says, Deliver him from going down to the pit: I have found a ransom.
B018C033V025	18	33	25	His flesh shall be younger than a childâ€™s: he shall return to the days of his youth:
B018C033V026	18	33	26	He shall pray unto God, and he will be favorable unto him: and he shall see his face with joy: for he will render unto man his righteousness.
B018C033V027	18	33	27	He looks upon men, and if any say, I have sinned, and perverted that which was right, and it profited me not;
B018C033V028	18	33	28	He will deliver his soul from going into the pit, and his life shall see the light.
B018C033V029	18	33	29	Lo, all these things works God twice, three times, with man,
B018C033V030	18	33	30	To bring back his soul from the pit, to be enlightened with the light of life.
B018C033V031	18	33	31	Mark well, O Job, hearken unto me: hold your peace, and I will speak.
B018C033V032	18	33	32	If you have any thing to say, answer me: speak, for I desire to justify you.
B018C033V033	18	33	33	If not, hearken unto me: hold your peace, and I shall teach you wisdom.
B018C034V001	18	34	1	Furthermore Elihu answered and said,
B018C034V002	18	34	2	Hear my words, O you wise men; and give ear unto me, you that have knowledge.
B018C034V003	18	34	3	For the ear tests words, as the mouth tastes food.
B018C034V004	18	34	4	Let us choose for us justice: let us know among ourselves what is good.
B018C034V005	18	34	5	For Job has said, I am righteous: and God has taken away my justice.
B018C034V006	18	34	6	Should I lie concerning my right? my wound is incurable though I am without transgression.
B018C034V007	18	34	7	What man is like Job, who drinks up scorn like water?
B018C034V008	18	34	8	Who goes in company with the workers of iniquity, and walks with wicked men.
B018C034V009	18	34	9	For he has said, It profits a man nothing that he should delight himself with God.
B018C034V010	18	34	10	Therefore hearken unto me, you men of understanding: far be it from God, that he should do wickedness; and from the Almighty, that he should commit iniquity.
B018C034V011	18	34	11	For the work of a man shall he render unto him, and cause every man to find according to his ways.
B018C034V012	18	34	12	Yea, surely God will not do wickedly, neither will the Almighty pervert justice.
B018C034V013	18	34	13	Who has given him charge over the earth? or who has laid on him the whole world?
B018C034V014	18	34	14	If he should set his heart upon man, if he should gather unto himself his spirit and his breath;
B018C034V015	18	34	15	All flesh would perish together, and man would turn again unto dust.
B018C034V016	18	34	16	If now you have understanding, hear this: hearken to the voice of my words.
B018C034V017	18	34	17	Shall even he that hates right govern? and will you condemn him that is most just?
B018C034V018	18	34	18	Is it fit to say to a king, You are wicked? and to princes, You are ungodly?
B018C034V019	18	34	19	How much less to him that regards not the persons of princes, nor regards the rich more than the poor? for they all are the work of his hands.
B018C034V020	18	34	20	In a moment shall they die, and the people shall be troubled at midnight, and pass away: and the mighty shall be taken away without a hand.
B018C034V021	18	34	21	For his eyes are upon the ways of man, and he sees all his steps.
B018C034V022	18	34	22	There is no darkness, nor shadow of death, where the workers of iniquity may hide themselves.
B018C034V023	18	34	23	For he will not lay upon man more than what is right; that he should enter into judgment with God.
B018C034V024	18	34	24	He shall break in pieces mighty men without number, and set others in their place.
B018C034V025	18	34	25	Therefore he knows their works, and he overturns them in the night, so that they are destroyed.
B018C034V026	18	34	26	He strikes them as wicked men in the open sight of others;
B018C034V027	18	34	27	Because they turned back from him, and would not consider any of his ways:
B018C034V028	18	34	28	So that they cause the cry of the poor to come unto him, and he hears the cry of the afflicted.
B018C034V029	18	34	29	When he gives quietness, who then can make trouble? and when he hides his face, who then can behold him? whether it be done against a nation, or against a man only:
B018C034V030	18	34	30	That the hypocrite reigns not, lest the people be ensnared.
B018C034V031	18	34	31	Surely it is fitting to be said unto God, I have borne chastisement, I will not offend any more:
B018C034V032	18	34	32	That which I see not you teach me: if I have done iniquity, I will do no more.
B018C034V033	18	34	33	Should it be according to your mind? he will recompense it, whether you refuse, or whether you choose; and not I: therefore declare what you know.
B018C034V034	18	34	34	Let men of understanding tell me, and let a wise man hearken unto me.
B018C034V035	18	34	35	Job has spoken without knowledge, and his words were without wisdom.
B018C034V036	18	34	36	My desire is that Job may be tried unto the end because he answers like wicked men.
B018C034V037	18	34	37	For he adds rebellion unto his sin, he claps his hands among us, and multiplies his words against God.
B018C035V001	18	35	1	Elihu spoke moreover, and said,
B018C035V002	18	35	2	Think you this to be right, that you said, My righteousness is more than Godâ€™s?
B018C035V003	18	35	3	For you said, What advantage will it be unto you? and, What profit shall I have, if I be cleansed from my sin?
B018C035V004	18	35	4	I will answer you, and your companions with you.
B018C035V005	18	35	5	Look unto the heavens, and see; and behold the clouds which are higher than you.
B018C035V006	18	35	6	If you sin, what do you accomplish against him? or if your transgressions are multiplied, what do you do unto him?
B018C035V007	18	35	7	If you are righteous, what give you to him? or what receives he of your hand?
B018C035V008	18	35	8	Your wickedness may hurt a man as you are; and your righteousness may profit the son of man.
B018C035V009	18	35	9	Because of the multitude of oppressions they make the oppressed to cry: they cry out because of the arm of the mighty.
B018C035V010	18	35	10	But none says, Where is God my maker, who gives songs in the night;
B018C035V011	18	35	11	Who teaches us more than the beasts of the earth, and makes us wiser than the fowls of heaven?
B018C035V012	18	35	12	There they cry, but none gives answer, because of the pride of evil men.
B018C035V013	18	35	13	Surely God will not hear vanity, neither will the Almighty regard it.
B018C035V014	18	35	14	Although you say you shall not see him, yet justice is before him; therefore you must trust in him.
B018C035V015	18	35	15	But now, because it is not so, he has visited in his anger; yet he knows it not in a great extreme:
B018C035V016	18	35	16	Therefore does Job open his mouth in vain; he multiplies words without knowledge.
B018C036V001	18	36	1	Elihu also proceeded, and said,
B018C036V002	18	36	2	Bear with me a little, and I will show you that I have yet to speak on Godâ€™s behalf.
B018C036V003	18	36	3	I will get my knowledge from afar, and will ascribe righteousness to my Maker.
B018C036V004	18	36	4	For truly my words shall not be false: he that is blameless in knowledge is with you.
B018C036V005	18	36	5	Behold, God is mighty, and despises no one: he is mighty in strength and wisdom.
B018C036V006	18	36	6	He preserves not the life of the wicked: but gives justice to the poor.
B018C036V007	18	36	7	He withdraws not his eyes from the righteous: but with kings they are on the throne; yea, he does establish them forever, and they are exalted.
B018C036V008	18	36	8	And if they are bound in fetters, and are held in cords of affliction;
B018C036V009	18	36	9	Then he shows them their work, and their transgressions, that they have exceeded.
B018C036V010	18	36	10	He opens also their ear to discipline, and commands that they return from iniquity.
B018C036V011	18	36	11	If they obey and serve him, they shall spend their days in prosperity, and their years in pleasures.
B018C036V012	18	36	12	But if they obey not, they shall perish by the sword, and they shall die without knowledge.
B018C036V013	18	36	13	But the hypocrites in heart heap up wrath: they cry not when he binds them.
B018C036V014	18	36	14	They die in youth, and their life is among the unclean.
B018C036V015	18	36	15	He delivers the poor in his affliction, and opens their ears in oppression.
B018C036V016	18	36	16	Even so would he have removed you out of the distress into a broad place, where there is no restraint; and that which should be set on your table should be full of richness.
B018C036V017	18	36	17	But you have fulfilled the judgment of the wicked: judgment and justice take hold on you.
B018C036V018	18	36	18	Because there is wrath, beware lest he take you away with one blow: then a great ransom cannot deliver you.
B018C036V019	18	36	19	Will he esteem your riches? no, not gold, nor all the forces of strength.
B018C036V020	18	36	20	Desire not the night, when people are cut off in their place.
B018C036V021	18	36	21	Take heed, regard not iniquity: for this have you chosen rather than affliction.
B018C036V022	18	36	22	Behold, God exalts by his power: who teaches like him?
B018C036V023	18	36	23	Who has prescribed him his way? or who can say, You have worked iniquity?
B018C036V024	18	36	24	Remember that you magnify his work, which men behold.
B018C036V025	18	36	25	Every man may see it; man may behold it afar off.
B018C036V026	18	36	26	Behold, God is great, and we know him not, neither can the number of his years be searched out.
B018C036V027	18	36	27	For he makes small the drops of water: they pour down rain according to its vapor:
B018C036V028	18	36	28	Which the clouds do drop and pour upon man abundantly.
B018C036V029	18	36	29	Also can any understand the spreadings of the clouds, or the thunder of his tabernacle?
B018C036V030	18	36	30	Behold, he spreads his lightning upon it, and covers the depths of the sea.
B018C036V031	18	36	31	For by them judges he the people; he gives food in abundance.
B018C036V032	18	36	32	With clouds he covers the light; and commands it not to shine by the cloud that comes between.
B018C036V033	18	36	33	The thunder thereof declares it, the cattle also, concerning the vapor.
B018C037V001	18	37	1	At this also my heart trembles, and is moved out of its place.
B018C037V002	18	37	2	Hear attentively the noise of his voice, and the sound that goes out of his mouth.
B018C037V003	18	37	3	He directs it under the whole heaven, and his lightning unto the ends of the earth.
B018C037V004	18	37	4	After it a voice roars: he thunders with the voice of his excellency; and he will not restrain them when his voice is heard.
B018C037V005	18	37	5	God thunders marvelously with his voice; great things does he, which we cannot comprehend.
B018C037V006	18	37	6	For he says to the snow, Be on the earth; likewise to the gentle rain, and to the heavy rain of his strength.
B018C037V007	18	37	7	He seals up the hand of every man; that all men may know his work.
B018C037V008	18	37	8	Then the beasts go into dens, and remain in their places.
B018C037V009	18	37	9	Out of the south comes the whirlwind: and cold out of the north.
B018C037V010	18	37	10	By the breath of God ice is given: and the broad waters are frozen.
B018C037V011	18	37	11	Also with moisture he loads the thick cloud: he scatters his bright cloud:
B018C037V012	18	37	12	And it is turned around by his guidance: that they may do whatsoever he commands them upon the face of the whole earth.
B018C037V013	18	37	13	He causes it to come, whether for correction, or for his land, or for mercy.
B018C037V014	18	37	14	Hearken unto this, O Job: stand still, and consider the wondrous works of God.
B018C037V015	18	37	15	Do you know when God dispatched them, and caused the light of his cloud to shine?
B018C037V016	18	37	16	Do you know the balancings of the clouds, the wondrous works of him who is blameless in knowledge?
B018C037V017	18	37	17	How your garments are warm, when he quiets the earth by the south wind?
B018C037V018	18	37	18	Have you with him spread out the sky, which is strong, and as a molten mirror?
B018C037V019	18	37	19	Teach us what we shall say unto him; for we cannot order our speech because of darkness.
B018C037V020	18	37	20	Shall it be told him that I speak? if a man speaks, surely he shall be swallowed up.
B018C037V021	18	37	21	And now men can not look on the bright light which is in the clouds: but the wind passes, and clears them.
B018C037V022	18	37	22	Fair weather comes out of the north: with God is awesome majesty.
B018C037V023	18	37	23	As for the Almighty, we cannot find him out: he is excellent in power, and in judgment, and in abundant justice: he will not afflict.
B018C037V024	18	37	24	Men do therefore fear him: he respects not any that are wise of heart.
