B044C025V026	44	25	26	Of whom I have no certain thing to write unto my lord. Therefore I have brought him forth before you, and specially before you, O king Agrippa, that, after examination, I might have somewhat to write.
B044C025V027	44	25	27	For it seems to me unreasonable to send a prisoner, and not to specify the crimes laid against him.
B044C026V001	44	26	1	Then Agrippa said unto Paul, You are permitted to speak for yourself. Then Paul stretched forth his hand, and answered for himself:
B044C026V002	44	26	2	I think myself happy, king Agrippa, because I shall answer for myself this day before you concerning all the things of which I am accused of the Jews:
B044C026V003	44	26	3	Especially because I know you to be expert in all customs and questions which are among the Jews: therefore I beseech you to hear me patiently.
B044C026V004	44	26	4	My manner of life from my youth, which was at the first among my own nation at Jerusalem, know all the Jews;
B044C026V005	44	26	5	Who knew me from the beginning, if they would testify, that after the most strict sect of our religion I lived a Pharisee.
B044C026V006	44	26	6	And now I stand and am judged for the hope of the promise made of God unto our fathers:
B044C026V007	44	26	7	Unto which promise our twelve tribes, instantly serving God day and night, hope to come. For which hope's sake, king Agrippa, I am accused of the Jews.
B044C026V008	44	26	8	Why should it be thought a thing incredible with you, that God should raise the dead?
B044C026V009	44	26	9	I verily thought with myself, that I ought to do many things contrary to the name of Jesus of Nazareth.
B044C026V010	44	26	10	Which thing I also did in Jerusalem: and many of the saints did I shut up in prison, having received authority from the chief priests; and when they were put to death, I gave my voice against them.
B044C026V011	44	26	11	And I punished them often in every synagogue, and compelled them to blaspheme; and being exceedingly mad against them, I persecuted them even unto foreign cities.
B044C026V012	44	26	12	Thus as I went to Damascus with authority and commission from the chief priests,
B044C026V013	44	26	13	At midday, O king, I saw in the way a light from heaven, above the brightness of the sun, shining round about me and them who journeyed with me.
B044C026V014	44	26	14	And when we were all fallen to the earth, I heard a voice speaking unto me, and saying in the Hebrew tongue, 
B044C026V015	44	26	15	And I said, Who are you, Lord? And he said, 
B044C026V016	44	26	16	
        
B044C026V017	44	26	17	
        
B044C026V018	44	26	18	
        
B044C026V019	44	26	19	Therefore, O king Agrippa, I was not disobedient unto the heavenly vision:
B044C026V020	44	26	20	But showed first unto them of Damascus, and at Jerusalem, and throughout all the country of Judea, and then to the Gentiles, that they should repent and turn to God, and do works befitting repentance.
B044C026V021	44	26	21	For these causes the Jews caught me in the temple, and went about to kill me.
B044C026V022	44	26	22	Having therefore obtained help of God, I continue unto this day, witnessing both to small and great, saying no other things than those which the prophets and Moses did say should come:
B044C026V023	44	26	23	That Christ should suffer, and that he should be the first that should rise from the dead, and should proclaim light unto the people, and to the Gentiles.
B044C026V024	44	26	24	And as he thus spoke for himself, Festus said with a loud voice, Paul, you are beside yourself; much learning does make you mad.
B044C026V025	44	26	25	But he said, I am not mad, most noble Festus; but speak forth the words of truth and good sense.
B044C026V026	44	26	26	For the king knows of these things, before whom also I speak freely: for I am persuaded that none of these things are hidden from him; for this thing was not done in a corner.
B044C026V027	44	26	27	King Agrippa, do you believe the prophets? I know that you believe.
B044C026V028	44	26	28	Then Agrippa said unto Paul, Almost you persuade me to be a Christian.
B044C026V029	44	26	29	And Paul said, I would to God, that not only you, but also all that hear me this day, were both almost, and altogether such as I am, except these bonds.
B044C026V030	44	26	30	And when he had thus spoken, the king rose up, and the governor, and Bernice, and they that sat with them:
B044C026V031	44	26	31	And when they were gone aside, they talked between themselves, saying, This man does nothing worthy of death or of bonds.
B044C026V032	44	26	32	Then said Agrippa unto Festus, This man might have been set at liberty, if he had not appealed unto Caesar.
B044C027V001	44	27	1	And when it was determined that we should sail to Italy, they delivered Paul and certain other prisoners unto one named Julius, a centurion of Augustus' band.
B044C027V002	44	27	2	And entering into a ship of Adramyttium, we embarked, meaning to sail by the coasts of Asia; one Aristarchus, a Macedonian of Thessalonica, being with us.
B044C027V003	44	27	3	And the next day we put in at Sidon. And Julius courteously treated Paul, and gave him liberty to go unto his friends to refresh himself.
B044C027V004	44	27	4	And when we had put to sea from there, we sailed close to Cyprus, because the winds were contrary.
B044C027V005	44	27	5	And when we had sailed over the sea near Cilicia and Pamphylia, we came to Myra, a city of Lycia.
B044C027V006	44	27	6	And there the centurion found a ship of Alexandria sailing to Italy; and he put us on it.
B044C027V007	44	27	7	And when we had sailed slowly many days, and were hardly come off Cnidus, the wind not allowing us, we sailed close to Crete, off Salmone;
B044C027V008	44	27	8	And, with difficulty passing it, came unto a place which is called The Fair Havens; near to which was the city of Lasea.
B044C027V009	44	27	9	Now when much time was spent, and when sailing was now dangerous, because the fast was now already past, Paul admonished them,
B044C027V010	44	27	10	And said unto them, Sirs, I perceive that this voyage will be with hurt and much damage, not only of the cargo and ship, but also of our lives.
B044C027V011	44	27	11	Nevertheless the centurion believed the captain and the owner of the ship, more than those things which were spoken by Paul.
B044C027V012	44	27	12	And because the haven was not suitable to winter in, the majority advised to depart from there also, if by any means they might arrive at Phoenix, and there to winter; which is a haven of Crete, and opens toward the southwest and northwest.
B044C027V013	44	27	13	And when the south wind blew softly, supposing that they had obtained their purpose, raising anchor, they sailed close by Crete.
B044C027V014	44	27	14	But not long after there arose against it a tempestuous wind, called Euroclydon.
B044C027V015	44	27	15	And when the ship was caught, and could not bear up into the wind, we let her be driven.
B044C027V016	44	27	16	And running under a certain island which is called Cauda, we had much work to secure the boat:
B044C027V017	44	27	17	Which when they had hoisted it, they used helps, undergirding the ship; and, fearing lest they should fall into the quicksand, struck sail, and so were driven.
B044C027V018	44	27	18	And we being exceedingly tossed with a tempest, the next day they lightened the ship;
B044C027V019	44	27	19	And the third day we cast out with our own hands the tackling of the ship.
B044C027V020	44	27	20	And when neither sun nor stars in many days appeared, and no small tempest lay on us, all hope that we should be saved was then taken away.
B044C027V021	44	27	21	But after long abstinence Paul stood forth in the midst of them, and said, Sirs, you should have hearkened unto me, and not have set sail from Crete, and to have gained this harm and loss.
B044C027V022	44	27	22	And now I exhort you to be of good cheer: for there shall be no loss of any man's life among you, but of the ship.
B044C027V023	44	27	23	For there stood by me this night the angel of God, whose I am, and whom I serve,
B044C027V024	44	27	24	Saying, Fear not, Paul; you must be brought before Caesar: and, lo, God has given you all them that sail with you.
B044C027V025	44	27	25	Therefore, sirs, be of good cheer: for I believe God, that it shall be even as it was told me.
B044C027V026	44	27	26	However we must be cast upon a certain island.
B044C027V027	44	27	27	But when the fourteenth night was come, as we were driven up and down in Adria, about midnight the sailors deemed that they drew near to some country;
B044C027V028	44	27	28	And sounded, and found it twenty fathoms: and when they had gone a little further, they sounded again, and found it fifteen fathoms.
B044C027V029	44	27	29	Then fearing lest we should have fallen upon rocks, they cast four anchors out of the stern, and wished for the day.
B044C027V030	44	27	30	And as the sailors were about to flee out of the ship, when they had let down the boat into the sea, under pretense as though they would have cast anchors out of the bow,
B044C027V031	44	27	31	Paul said to the centurion and to the soldiers, Except these abide in the ship, you cannot be saved.
B044C027V032	44	27	32	Then the soldiers cut off the ropes of the boat, and let her fall off.
B044C027V033	44	27	33	And while the day was coming on, Paul besought them all to take food, saying, This day is the fourteenth day that you have tarried and continued fasting, having taken nothing.
B044C027V034	44	27	34	Therefore I pray you to take some food: for this is for your health: for there shall not a hair fall from the head of any of you.
B044C027V035	44	27	35	And when he had thus spoken, he took bread, and gave thanks to God in the presence of them all: and when he had broken it, he began to eat.
B044C027V036	44	27	36	Then were they all of good cheer, and they also took some food.
B044C027V037	44	27	37	And we were in all in the ship two hundred and seventy-six souls.
B044C027V038	44	27	38	And when they had eaten enough, they lightened the ship, and cast out the wheat into the sea.
B044C027V039	44	27	39	And when it was day, they knew not the land: but they discovered a certain bay with a shore, into which they were minded, if it were possible, to drive in the ship.
B044C027V040	44	27	40	And when they had taken up the anchors, they committed themselves unto the sea, and released the rudder bands, and hoisted up the foresail to the wind, and made toward shore.
B044C027V041	44	27	41	And falling into a place where two seas met, they ran the ship aground; and the bow stuck fast, and remained unmovable, but the stern was broken with the violence of the waves.
B044C027V042	44	27	42	And the soldiers' plan was to kill the prisoners, lest any of them should swim out, and escape.
B044C027V043	44	27	43	But the centurion, willing to save Paul, kept them from their purpose; and commanded that they who could swim should cast themselves first into the sea, and get to land:
B044C027V044	44	27	44	And the rest, some on boards, and some on broken pieces of the ship. And so it came to pass, that they escaped all safe to land.
B044C028V001	44	28	1	And when they were escaped, then they knew that the island was called Malta.
B044C028V002	44	28	2	And the native people showed us no little kindness: for they kindled a fire, and received us every one, because of the present rain, and because of the cold.
B044C028V003	44	28	3	And when Paul had gathered a bundle of sticks, and laid them on the fire, there came a viper out of the heat, and fastened on his hand.
B044C028V004	44	28	4	And when the natives saw the creature hang on his hand, they said among themselves, No doubt this man is a murderer, whom, though he has escaped the sea, yet justice allows not to live.
B044C028V005	44	28	5	And he shook off the creature into the fire, and felt no harm.
B044C028V006	44	28	6	However they looked when he should have swollen, or fallen down dead suddenly: but after they had looked a great while, and saw no harm come to him, they changed their minds, and said that he was a god.
B044C028V007	44	28	7	In the same place were lands of the chief man of the island, whose name was Publius; who received us, and lodged us three days courteously.
B044C028V008	44	28	8	And it came to pass, that the father of Publius lay sick of a fever and of dysentery: to whom Paul entered in, and prayed, and laid his hands on him, and healed him.
B044C028V009	44	28	9	So when this was done, others also, who had diseases in the island, came, and were healed:
B044C028V010	44	28	10	Who also honored us with many honors; and when we departed, they put on board such things as were necessary.
B044C028V011	44	28	11	And after three months we departed in a ship of Alexandria, which had wintered in the isle, whose sign was Castor and Pollux.
B044C028V012	44	28	12	And landing at Syracuse, we tarried there three days.
B044C028V013	44	28	13	And from there we set a course, and came to Rhegium: and after one day the south wind blew, and we came the next day to Puteoli:
B044C028V014	44	28	14	Where we found brethren, and were invited to tarry with them seven days: and so we went toward Rome.
B044C028V015	44	28	15	And from there, when the brethren heard of us, they came to meet us as far as the Appii Forum, and The Three Taverns: whom when Paul saw, he thanked God, and took courage.
B044C028V016	44	28	16	And when we came to Rome, the centurion delivered the prisoners to the captain of the guard: but Paul was allowed to dwell by himself with a soldier that kept him.
B044C028V017	44	28	17	And it came to pass, that after three days Paul called the chief of the Jews together: and when they were come together, he said unto them, Men and brethren, though I have committed nothing against the people, or customs of our fathers, yet was I delivered prisoner from Jerusalem into the hands of the Romans.
B044C028V018	44	28	18	Who, when they had examined me, would have let me go, because there was no cause of death in me.
B044C028V019	44	28	19	But when the Jews spoke against it, I was constrained to appeal unto Caesar; not that I had anything to accuse my nation of.
B044C028V020	44	28	20	For this cause therefore have I called for you, to see you, and to speak with you: because for the hope of Israel I am bound with this chain.
B044C028V021	44	28	21	And they said unto him, We neither received letters out of Judea concerning you, neither any of the brethren that came showed or spoke any harm of you.
B044C028V022	44	28	22	But we desire to hear of you what you think: for as concerning this sect, we know that everywhere it is spoken against.
B044C028V023	44	28	23	And when they had appointed him a day, there came many to him into his lodging; to whom he expounded and testified of the kingdom of God, persuading them concerning Jesus, both out of the law of Moses, and out of the prophets, from morning till evening.
B044C028V024	44	28	24	And some believed the things which were spoken, and some believed not.
B044C028V025	44	28	25	And when they agreed not among themselves, they departed, after Paul had spoken one word, Well spoke the Holy Spirit by Isaiah the prophet unto our fathers,
B044C028V026	44	28	26	Saying, 
B044C028V027	44	28	27	
        
B044C028V028	44	28	28	Be it known therefore unto you, that the salvation of God is sent unto the Gentiles, and that they will hear it.
B044C028V029	44	28	29	And when he had said these words, the Jews departed, and had much dispute among themselves.
B044C028V030	44	28	30	And Paul dwelt two whole years in his own hired house, and received all that came in unto him,
B044C028V031	44	28	31	Preaching the kingdom of God, and teaching those things which concern the Lord Jesus Christ, with all confidence, no man forbidding him.
B045C001V001	45	1	1	Paul, a servant of Jesus Christ, called to be an apostle, separated unto the gospel of God,
B045C001V002	45	1	2	(Which he had promised before by his prophets in the holy scriptures,)
B045C001V003	45	1	3	Concerning his Son Jesus Christ our Lord, who was made of the descendants of David according to the flesh;
B045C001V004	45	1	4	And declared to be the Son of God with power, according to the Spirit of holiness, by the resurrection from the dead:
B045C001V005	45	1	5	By whom we have received grace and apostleship, for obedience to the faith among all nations, for his name:
B045C001V006	45	1	6	Among whom are you also the called of Jesus Christ:
B045C001V007	45	1	7	To all that be in Rome, beloved of God, called to be saints: Grace to you and peace from God our Father, and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B045C001V008	45	1	8	First, I thank my God through Jesus Christ for you all, that your faith is spoken of throughout the whole world.
B045C001V009	45	1	9	For God is my witness, whom I serve with my spirit in the gospel of his Son, that without ceasing I make mention of you always in my prayers;
B045C001V010	45	1	10	Making request, if by any means now at last I might have a prosperous journey by the will of God to come unto you.
B045C001V011	45	1	11	For I long to see you, that I may impart unto you some spiritual gift, to the end you may be established;
B045C001V012	45	1	12	That is, that I may be comforted together with you by the mutual faith both of you and me.
B045C001V013	45	1	13	Now I would not have you ignorant, brethren, that often I purposed to come unto you, (but was prevented thus far,) that I might have some fruit among you also, even as among other Gentiles.
B045C001V014	45	1	14	I am debtor both to the Greeks, and to the Barbarians; both to the wise, and to the unwise.
B045C001V015	45	1	15	So, as much as in me is, I am ready to preach the gospel to you that are at Rome also.
B045C001V016	45	1	16	For I am not ashamed of the gospel of Christ: for it is the power of God unto salvation to every one that believes; to the Jew first, and also to the Greek.
B045C001V017	45	1	17	For in it is the righteousness of God revealed from faith to faith: as it is written, The just shall live by faith.
B045C001V018	45	1	18	For the wrath of God is revealed from heaven against all ungodliness and unrighteousness of men, who hold the truth in unrighteousness;
B045C001V019	45	1	19	Because that which may be known of God is manifest in them; for God has showed it unto them.
B045C001V020	45	1	20	For the invisible things of him from the creation of the world are clearly seen, being understood by the things that are made, even his eternal power and deity; so that they are without excuse:
B045C001V021	45	1	21	Because, when they knew God, they glorified him not as God, neither were thankful; but became vain in their imaginations, and their foolish hearts were darkened.
B045C001V022	45	1	22	Professing themselves to be wise, they became fools,
B045C001V023	45	1	23	And changed the glory of the incorruptible God into an image made like to corruptible man, and to birds, and four-footed beasts, and creeping things.
B045C001V024	45	1	24	Therefore God also gave them up to uncleanness through the lusts of their own hearts, to dishonor their own bodies between themselves:
B045C001V025	45	1	25	Who changed the truth of God into a lie, and worshiped and served the creature more than the Creator, who is blessed forever. Amen.
B045C001V026	45	1	26	For this cause God gave them up unto vile affections: for even their women did change the natural use into that which is against nature:
B045C001V027	45	1	27	And likewise also the men, leaving the natural use of the woman, burned in their lust one toward another; men with men working that which is shameful, and receiving in themselves that recompense of their error which was fitting.
B045C001V028	45	1	28	And even as they did not like to retain God in their knowledge, God gave them over to a reprobate mind, to do those things which are not proper;
B045C001V029	45	1	29	Being filled with all unrighteousness, fornication, wickedness, covetousness, maliciousness; full of envy, murder, debate, deceit, malignity; whisperers,
B045C001V030	45	1	30	Backbiters, haters of God, despiteful, proud, boasters, inventors of evil things, disobedient to parents,
B045C001V031	45	1	31	Without understanding, covenant breakers, without natural affection, implacable, unmerciful:
B045C001V032	45	1	32	Who knowing the judgment of God, that they who commit such things are worthy of death, not only do the same, but have pleasure in them that do them.
B045C002V001	45	2	1	Therefore you are inexcusable, O man, whosoever you are that judge: for in what you judge another, you condemn yourself; for you that judge do the same things.
B045C002V002	45	2	2	But we are sure that the judgment of God is according to truth against them who commit such things.
B045C002V003	45	2	3	And do you think, O man, that judge them who do such things, and do the same, that you shall escape the judgment of God?
B045C002V004	45	2	4	Or despise you the riches of his goodness and forbearance and longsuffering; not knowing that the goodness of God leads you to repentance?
B045C002V005	45	2	5	But according to your hardness and unrepentant heart treasure up unto yourself wrath against the day of wrath and revelation of the righteous judgment of God;
B045C002V006	45	2	6	Who will render to every man according to his deeds:
B045C002V007	45	2	7	To them who by patient continuance in well doing seek for glory and honor and immortality, eternal life:
B045C002V008	45	2	8	But unto them that are contentious, and do not obey the truth, but obey unrighteousness, indignation and wrath,
B045C002V009	45	2	9	Tribulation and anguish, upon every soul of man that does evil, of the Jew first, and also of the Greek;
B045C002V010	45	2	10	But glory, honor, and peace, to every man that works good, to the Jew first, and also to the Greek:
B045C002V011	45	2	11	For there is no respect of persons with God.
B045C002V012	45	2	12	For as many as have sinned without law shall also perish without law: and as many as have sinned in the law shall be judged by the law;
B045C002V013	45	2	13	(For not the hearers of the law are just before God, but the doers of the law shall be justified.
B045C002V014	45	2	14	For when the Gentiles, who have not the law, do by nature the things contained in the law, these, having not the law, are a law unto themselves:
B045C002V015	45	2	15	Who show the work of the law written in their hearts, their conscience also bearing witness, and their thoughts the mean while accusing or else excusing one another;)
B045C002V016	45	2	16	In the day when God shall judge the secrets of men by Jesus Christ according to my gospel.
B045C002V017	45	2	17	Behold, you are called a Jew, and rest in the law, and make your boast of God,
B045C002V018	45	2	18	And know his will, and approve the things that are more excellent, being instructed out of the law;
B045C002V019	45	2	19	And are confident that you yourself are a guide of the blind, a light of them who are in darkness,
B045C002V020	45	2	20	An instructor of the foolish, a teacher of babes, who has the form of knowledge and of the truth in the law.
B045C002V021	45	2	21	You therefore who teach another, can you not teach yourself? you that preach a man should not steal, do you steal?
B045C002V022	45	2	22	You that say a man should not commit adultery, do you commit adultery? you that abhor idols, do you commit sacrilege?
B045C002V023	45	2	23	You that make your boast of the law, through breaking the law do you dishonor God?
B045C002V024	45	2	24	
        
B045C002V025	45	2	25	For circumcision verily profits, if you keep the law: but if you are a breaker of the law, your circumcision is made uncircumcision.
B045C002V026	45	2	26	Therefore if the uncircumcision keeps the righteousness of the law, shall not his uncircumcision be counted for circumcision?
B045C002V027	45	2	27	And shall not uncircumcision which is by nature, if it fulfills the law, judge you, who by the letter and circumcision do transgress the law?
B045C002V028	45	2	28	For he is not a Jew, who is one outwardly; neither is that circumcision, which is outward in the flesh:
B045C002V029	45	2	29	But he is a Jew, who is one inwardly; and circumcision is that of the heart, in the spirit, and not in the letter; whose praise is not of men, but of God.
B045C003V001	45	3	1	What advantage then has the Jew? or what profit is there of circumcision?
B045C003V002	45	3	2	Much every way: chiefly, because unto them were committed the oracles of God.
B045C003V003	45	3	3	For what if some did not believe? shall their unbelief make the faithfulness of God without effect?
B045C003V004	45	3	4	God forbid: yea, let God be true, but every man a liar; as it is written, That you might be justified in your sayings, and might overcome when you are judged.
B045C003V005	45	3	5	But if our unrighteousness commends the righteousness of God, what shall we say? Is God unrighteous who takes vengeance? (I speak as a man)
B045C003V006	45	3	6	God forbid: for then how shall God judge the world?
B045C003V007	45	3	7	For if the truth of God has more abounded through my lie unto his glory; why yet am I also judged as a sinner?
B045C003V008	45	3	8	And not rather, (as we are slanderously reported, and as some affirm that we say,) Let us do evil, that good may come? whose condemnation is just.
B045C003V009	45	3	9	What then? are we better than they? No, in no way: for we have before proved both Jews and Greeks, that they are all under sin;
B045C003V010	45	3	10	As it is written, There is none righteous, no, not one:
B045C003V011	45	3	11	There is none that understands, there is none that seeks after God.
B045C003V012	45	3	12	They are all gone out of the way, they are together become unprofitable; there is none that does good, no, not one.
B045C003V013	45	3	13	Their throat is an open sepulcher; with their tongues they have used deceit; the poison of asps is under their lips:
B045C003V014	45	3	14	Whose mouth is full of cursing and bitterness:
B045C003V015	45	3	15	Their feet are swift to shed blood:
B045C003V016	45	3	16	Destruction and misery are in their ways:
B045C003V017	45	3	17	And the way of peace have they not known:
B045C003V018	45	3	18	There is no fear of God before their eyes.
B045C003V019	45	3	19	Now we know that whatsoever things the law says, it says to them who are under the law: that every mouth may be stopped, and all the world may become guilty before God.
B045C003V020	45	3	20	Therefore by the deeds of the law there shall no flesh be justified in his sight: for by the law is the knowledge of sin.
B045C003V021	45	3	21	But now the righteousness of God apart from the law is manifested, being witnessed by the law and the prophets;
B045C003V022	45	3	22	Even the righteousness of God which is by faith in Jesus Christ unto all and upon all them that believe: for there is no difference:
B045C003V023	45	3	23	For all have sinned, and come short of the glory of God;
B045C003V024	45	3	24	Being justified freely by his grace through the redemption that is in Christ Jesus:
B045C003V025	45	3	25	Whom God has set forth to be a propitiation through faith in his blood, to declare his righteousness for the remission of sins that are past, through the forbearance of God;
B045C003V026	45	3	26	To declare, I say, at this time his righteousness: that he might be just, and the justifier of him who believes in Jesus.
B045C003V027	45	3	27	Where is boasting then? It is excluded. By what law? of works? Nay: but by the law of faith.
B045C003V028	45	3	28	Therefore we conclude that a man is justified by faith without the deeds of the law.
B045C003V029	45	3	29	Is he the God of the Jews only? is he not also of the Gentiles? Yes, of the Gentiles also:
B045C003V030	45	3	30	Seeing it is one God, who shall justify the circumcision by faith, and uncircumcision through faith.
B045C003V031	45	3	31	Do we then make void the law through faith? God forbid: yea, we establish the law.
B045C004V001	45	4	1	What shall we say then that Abraham our father, as pertaining to the flesh, has found?
B045C004V002	45	4	2	For if Abraham were justified by works, he has something in which to boast; but not before God.
B045C004V003	45	4	3	For what says the scripture? Abraham believed God, and it was counted unto him for righteousness.
B045C004V004	45	4	4	Now to him that works is the reward not reckoned of grace, but of debt.
B045C004V005	45	4	5	But to him that works not, but believes on him that justifies the ungodly, his faith is counted for righteousness.
B045C004V006	45	4	6	Even as David also describes the blessedness of the man, unto whom God imputes righteousness without works,
B045C004V007	45	4	7	Saying, Blessed are they whose iniquities are forgiven, and whose sins are covered.
B045C004V008	45	4	8	Blessed is the man to whom the Lord will not impute sin.
B045C004V009	45	4	9	Comes this blessedness then upon the circumcision only, or upon the uncircumcision also? for we say that faith was reckoned to Abraham for righteousness.
B045C004V010	45	4	10	How was it then reckoned? when he was in circumcision, or in uncircumcision? Not in circumcision, but in uncircumcision.
B045C004V011	45	4	11	And he received the sign of circumcision, a seal of the righteousness of the faith which he had yet being uncircumcised: that he might be the father of all them that believe, though they be not circumcised; that righteousness might be imputed unto them also:
B045C004V012	45	4	12	And the father of circumcision to them who are not of the circumcision only, but who also walk in the steps of that faith of our father Abraham, which he had being yet uncircumcised.
B045C004V013	45	4	13	For the promise, that he should be the heir of the world, was not to Abraham, or to his descendants, through the law, but through the righteousness of faith.
B045C004V014	45	4	14	For if they who are of the law be heirs, faith is made void, and the promise made of none effect:
B045C004V015	45	4	15	Because the law works wrath: for where no law is, there is no transgression.
B045C004V016	45	4	16	Therefore it is of faith, that it might be by grace; to the end the promise might be sure to all the descendants; not to those only who are of the law, but to those also who are of the faith of Abraham; who is the father of us all,
B045C004V017	45	4	17	(As it is written, 
B045C004V018	45	4	18	Who against hope believed in hope, that he might become the father of many nations, according to that which was spoken, 
B045C004V019	45	4	19	And being not weak in faith, he considered not his own body as now dead, when he was about a hundred years old, neither yet the deadness of Sarah's womb:
B045C004V020	45	4	20	He staggered not at the promise of God through unbelief; but was strong in faith, giving glory to God;
B045C004V021	45	4	21	And being fully persuaded that, what he had promised, he was able also to perform.
B045C004V022	45	4	22	And therefore it was imputed to him for righteousness.
B045C004V023	45	4	23	Now it was not written for his sake alone, that it was imputed to him;
B045C004V024	45	4	24	But for us also, to whom it shall be imputed, if we believe on him that raised up Jesus our Lord from the dead;
B045C004V025	45	4	25	Who was delivered for our offenses, and was raised again for our justification.
B045C005V001	45	5	1	Therefore being justified by faith, we have peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ:
B045C005V002	45	5	2	By whom also we have access by faith into this grace in which we stand, and rejoice in hope of the glory of God.
B045C005V003	45	5	3	And not only so, but we glory in tribulations also: knowing that tribulation works patience;
B045C005V004	45	5	4	And patience, experience; and experience, hope:
B045C005V005	45	5	5	And hope makes not ashamed; because the love of God is shed abroad in our hearts by the Holy Spirit who is given unto us.
B045C005V006	45	5	6	For when we were yet without strength, in due time Christ died for the ungodly.
B045C005V007	45	5	7	For scarcely for a righteous man will one die: yet perhaps for a good man some would even dare to die.
B045C005V008	45	5	8	But God commends his love toward us, in that, while we were yet sinners, Christ died for us.
B045C005V009	45	5	9	Much more then, being now justified by his blood, we shall be saved from wrath through him.
B045C005V010	45	5	10	For if, when we were enemies, we were reconciled to God by the death of his Son, much more, being reconciled, we shall be saved by his life.
B045C005V011	45	5	11	And not only so, but we also rejoice in God through our Lord Jesus Christ, by whom we have now received the reconciliation.
B045C005V012	45	5	12	Therefore, as by one man sin entered into the world, and death by sin; and so death passed upon all men, for that all have sinned:
B045C005V013	45	5	13	(For until the law sin was in the world: but sin is not imputed when there is no law.
B045C005V014	45	5	14	Nevertheless death reigned from Adam to Moses, even over them that had not sinned in the likeness of Adam's transgression, who is the figure of him that was to come.
B045C005V015	45	5	15	So also is the free gift not like the offense. For if through the offense of one many are dead, much more the grace of God, and the gift by grace, which is by one man, Jesus Christ, has abounded unto many.
B045C005V016	45	5	16	So is the gift not like it was by one that sinned: for the judgment was by one to condemnation, but the free gift is of many offenses unto justification.
B045C005V017	45	5	17	For if by one man's offense death reigned by one; much more they who receive abundance of grace and of the gift of righteousness shall reign in life by one, Jesus Christ.)
B045C005V018	45	5	18	Therefore as by the offense of one judgment came upon all men to condemnation; even so by the righteousness of one the free gift came upon all men unto justification of life.
B045C005V019	45	5	19	For as by one man's disobedience many were made sinners, so by the obedience of one shall many be made righteous.
B045C005V020	45	5	20	Moreover the law entered, that the offense might abound. But where sin abounded, grace did much more abound:
B045C005V021	45	5	21	That as sin has reigned unto death, even so might grace reign through righteousness unto eternal life by Jesus Christ our Lord.
B045C006V001	45	6	1	What shall we say then? Shall we continue in sin, that grace may abound?
B045C006V002	45	6	2	God forbid. How shall we, that are dead to sin, live any longer in it?
B045C006V003	45	6	3	Know you not, that so many of us as were baptized into Jesus Christ were baptized into his death?
B045C006V004	45	6	4	Therefore we are buried with him by baptism into death: that just as Christ was raised up from the dead by the glory of the Father, even so we also should walk in newness of life.
B045C006V005	45	6	5	For if we have been united with him in the likeness of his death, we shall be also in the likeness of his resurrection:
B045C006V006	45	6	6	Knowing this, that our old man is crucified with him, that the body of sin might be destroyed, that we should no longer serve sin.
B045C006V007	45	6	7	For he that is dead is freed from sin.
B045C006V008	45	6	8	Now if we are dead with Christ, we believe that we shall also live with him:
B045C006V009	45	6	9	Knowing that Christ being raised from the dead dies no more; death has no more dominion over him.
B045C006V010	45	6	10	For in that he died, he died unto sin once: but in that he lives, he lives unto God.
B045C006V011	45	6	11	Likewise reckon you also yourselves to be dead indeed unto sin, but alive unto God through Jesus Christ our Lord.
B045C006V012	45	6	12	Let not sin therefore reign in your mortal body, that you should obey it in its lusts.
B045C006V013	45	6	13	Neither yield your members as instruments of unrighteousness unto sin: but yield yourselves unto God, as those that are alive from the dead, and your members as instruments of righteousness unto God.
B045C006V014	45	6	14	For sin shall not have dominion over you: for you are not under the law, but under grace.
B045C006V015	45	6	15	What then? shall we sin, because we are not under the law, but under grace? God forbid.
B045C006V016	45	6	16	Know you not, that to whom you yield yourselves servants to obey, his servants you are to whom you obey; whether of sin unto death, or of obedience unto righteousness?
B045C006V017	45	6	17	But God be thanked, that you were the servants of sin, but you have obeyed from the heart that form of doctrine which was delivered you.
B045C006V018	45	6	18	Being then made free from sin, you became the servants of righteousness.
B045C006V019	45	6	19	I speak after the manner of men because of the weakness of your flesh: for as you have yielded your members servants to uncleanness and to iniquity unto iniquity; even so now yield your members servants to righteousness unto holiness.
B045C006V020	45	6	20	For when you were the servants of sin, you were free from righteousness.
B045C006V021	45	6	21	What fruit had you then in those things of which you are now ashamed? for the end of those things is death.
B045C006V022	45	6	22	But now being made free from sin, and become servants to God, you have your fruit unto holiness, and the end everlasting life.
B045C006V023	45	6	23	For the wages of sin is death; but the gift of God is eternal life through Jesus Christ our Lord.
B045C007V001	45	7	1	Know you not, brethren, (for I speak to them that know the law,) how that the law has dominion over a man as long as he lives?
B045C007V002	45	7	2	For the woman who has a husband is bound by the law to her husband so long as he lives; but if the husband dies, she is loosed from the law of her husband.
B045C007V003	45	7	3	So then if, while her husband lives, she is married to another man, she shall be called an adulteress: but if her husband dies, she is free from that law; so that she is no adulteress, though she is married to another man.
B045C007V004	45	7	4	Therefore, my brethren, you also have become dead to the law by the body of Christ; that you should be married to another, even to him who is raised from the dead, that we should bring forth fruit unto God.
B045C007V005	45	7	5	For when we were in the flesh, the passions of sins, which were by the law, did work in our members to bring forth fruit unto death.
B045C007V006	45	7	6	But now we are delivered from the law, being dead to that in which we were held; that we should serve in newness of spirit, and not in the oldness of the letter.
B045C007V007	45	7	7	What shall we say then? is the law sin? God forbid. Nay, I had not known sin, but by the law: for I had not known lust, except the law had said, you shall not covet.
B045C007V008	45	7	8	But sin, taking occasion by the commandment, worked in me all manner of covetousness. For without the law sin was dead.
B045C007V009	45	7	9	For I was alive apart from the law once: but when the commandment came, sin revived, and I died.
B045C007V010	45	7	10	And the commandment, which was ordained to life, I found to be unto death.
B045C007V011	45	7	11	For sin, taking occasion by the commandment, deceived me, and by it slew me.
B045C007V012	45	7	12	Therefore the law is holy, and the commandment holy, and just, and good.
B045C007V013	45	7	13	Was then that which is good made death unto me? God forbid. But sin, that it might appear sin, working death in me by that which is good; that sin by the commandment might become exceedingly sinful.
B045C007V014	45	7	14	For we know that the law is spiritual: but I am carnal, sold under sin.
B045C007V015	45	7	15	For that which I do I know not: for what I would, that do I not; but what I hate, that do I.
B045C007V016	45	7	16	If then I do that which I would not, I consent unto the law that it is good.
B045C007V017	45	7	17	Now then it is no more I that do it, but sin that dwells in me.
B045C007V018	45	7	18	For I know that in me (that is, in my flesh,) dwells no good thing: for to will is present with me; but how to perform that which is good I find not.
B045C007V019	45	7	19	For the good that I would I do not: but the evil which I would not, that I do.
B045C007V020	45	7	20	Now if I do that which I would not, it is no more I that do it, but sin that dwells in me.
B045C007V021	45	7	21	I find then a law, that, when I would do good, evil is present with me.
B045C007V022	45	7	22	For I delight in the law of God after the inward man:
B045C007V023	45	7	23	But I see another law in my members, warring against the law of my mind, and bringing me into captivity to the law of sin which is in my members.
B045C007V024	45	7	24	O wretched man that I am! who shall deliver me from the body of this death?
B045C007V025	45	7	25	I thank God through Jesus Christ our Lord. So then with the mind I myself serve the law of God; but with the flesh the law of sin.
B045C008V001	45	8	1	There is therefore now no condemnation to them who are in Christ Jesus, who walk not after the flesh, but after the Spirit.
B045C008V002	45	8	2	For the law of the Spirit of life in Christ Jesus has made me free from the law of sin and death.
B045C008V003	45	8	3	For what the law could not do, in that it was weak through the flesh, God sending his own Son in the likeness of sinful flesh, and for sin, condemned sin in the flesh:
B045C008V004	45	8	4	That the righteousness of the law might be fulfilled in us, who walk not after the flesh, but after the Spirit.
B045C008V005	45	8	5	For they that are after the flesh do mind the things of the flesh; but they that are after the Spirit the things of the Spirit.
B045C008V006	45	8	6	For to be carnally minded is death; but to be spiritually minded is life and peace.
B045C008V007	45	8	7	Because the carnal mind is enmity against God: for it is not subject to the law of God, neither indeed can be.
B045C008V008	45	8	8	So then they that are in the flesh cannot please God.
B045C008V009	45	8	9	But you are not in the flesh, but in the Spirit, if so be that the Spirit of God dwells in you. Now if any man have not the Spirit of Christ, he is none of his.
B045C008V010	45	8	10	And if Christ be in you, the body is dead because of sin; but the Spirit is life because of righteousness.
B045C008V011	45	8	11	But if the Spirit of him that raised up Jesus from the dead dwells in you, he that raised up Christ from the dead shall also bring to life your mortal bodies by his Spirit that dwells in you.
B045C008V012	45	8	12	Therefore, brethren, we are debtors, not to the flesh, to live after the flesh.
B045C008V013	45	8	13	For if you live after the flesh, you shall die: but if you through the Spirit do put to death the deeds of the body, you shall live.
B045C008V014	45	8	14	For as many as are led by the Spirit of God, they are the sons of God.
B045C008V015	45	8	15	For you have not received the spirit of bondage again to fear; but you have received the Spirit of adoption, by which we cry, Abba, Father.
B045C008V016	45	8	16	The Spirit himself bears witness with our spirit, that we are the children of God:
B045C008V017	45	8	17	And if children, then heirs; heirs of God, and joint-heirs with Christ; if so be that we suffer with him, so that we may be also glorified together.
B045C008V018	45	8	18	For I reckon that the sufferings of this present time are not worthy to be compared with the glory which shall be revealed in us.
B045C008V019	45	8	19	For the earnest expectation of the creation waits for the manifestation of the sons of God.
B045C008V020	45	8	20	For the creation was made subject to vanity, not willingly, but by reason of him who has subjected the same in hope,
B045C008V021	45	8	21	Because the creation itself also shall be delivered from the bondage of corruption into the glorious liberty of the children of God.
B045C008V022	45	8	22	For we know that the whole creation groans and travails in pain together until now.
B045C008V023	45	8	23	And not only they, but ourselves also, who have the firstfruits of the Spirit, even we ourselves groan within ourselves, waiting for the adoption, that is, the redemption of our body.
B045C008V024	45	8	24	For we are saved by hope: but hope that is seen is not hope: for what a man sees, why does he yet hope for?
B045C008V025	45	8	25	But if we hope for that we see not, then do we with patience wait for it.
B045C008V026	45	8	26	Likewise the Spirit also helps our weakness: for we know not what we should pray for as we ought but the Spirit himself makes intercession for us with groanings which cannot be uttered.
B045C008V027	45	8	27	And he that searches the hearts knows what is the mind of the Spirit, because he makes intercession for the saints according to the will of God.
B045C008V028	45	8	28	And we know that all things work together for good to them that love God, to them who are the called according to his purpose.
B045C008V029	45	8	29	For whom he did foreknow, he also did predestinate to be conformed to the image of his Son, that he might be the firstborn among many brethren.
B045C008V030	45	8	30	Moreover whom he did predestinate, them he also called: and whom he called, them he also justified: and whom he justified, them he also glorified.
B045C008V031	45	8	31	What shall we then say to these things? If God is for us, who can be against us?
B045C008V032	45	8	32	He that spared not his own Son, but delivered him up for us all, how shall he not with him also freely give us all things?
B045C008V033	45	8	33	Who shall lay anything to the charge of God's elect? It is God that justifies.
B045C008V034	45	8	34	Who is he that condemns? It is Christ that died, yea rather, that is risen again, who is even at the right hand of God, who also makes intercession for us.
B045C008V035	45	8	35	Who shall separate us from the love of Christ? shall tribulation, or distress, or persecution, or famine, or nakedness, or peril, or sword?
B045C008V036	45	8	36	As it is written, For your sake we are killed all the day long; we are accounted as sheep for the slaughter.
B045C008V037	45	8	37	Nay, in all these things we are more than conquerors through him that loved us.
B045C008V038	45	8	38	For I am persuaded, that neither death, nor life, nor angels, nor principalities, nor powers, nor things present, nor things to come,
B045C008V039	45	8	39	Nor height, nor depth, nor any other creation, shall be able to separate us from the love of God, which is in Christ Jesus our Lord.
